const TOPIC_DESCS = {"Somalia":{"desc":"Somalia is a country located on the Horn of Africa, along the eastern coast of the continent. It has faced decades of civil war and instability since the collapse of its central government in 1991. Somalia was an important trading center in ancient times, known to the Egyptians as the 'Land of Punt,' and it was colonized by both Italy and Britain before gaining independence in 1960.","facts":["Located on the Horn of Africa with the longest coastline on the African mainland","Ancient Somalis traded with Egypt, Rome, and China","Gained independence in 1960 by uniting British and Italian Somaliland","Civil war began in 1991 after the overthrow of dictator Siad Barre","The capital city is Mogadishu"]},"Battle of Waterloo":{"desc":"The Battle of Waterloo was fought on June 18, 1815, in present-day Belgium. It was the final defeat of Napoleon Bonaparte by British and Prussian forces led by the Duke of Wellington and Gebhard von Blucher. This battle ended the Napoleonic Wars and Napoleon was exiled to the island of Saint Helena, where he died in 1821.","facts":["Fought on June 18, 1815 near Brussels, Belgium","Napoleon faced the Duke of Wellington (British) and Blucher (Prussian)","Napoleon's last major battle before his final exile","The word 'Waterloo' now means a decisive defeat","Led to the Congress of Vienna reshaping Europe"]},"Mansa Musa":{"desc":"Mansa Musa was the emperor of the Mali Empire in West Africa during the 14th century. He is often considered the wealthiest person in history. His famous pilgrimage to Mecca in 1324 was so lavish that he gave away so much gold it crashed the economy of Egypt for years.","facts":["Ruled the Mali Empire from about 1312 to 1337","Often called the richest person who ever lived","His 1324 pilgrimage to Mecca included 60,000 people and 80 camels carrying gold","He gave away so much gold in Cairo that it caused inflation for over a decade","Built the famous Djinguereber Mosque in Timbuktu"]},"Philippines":{"desc":"The Philippines is an archipelago of over 7,000 islands in Southeast Asia. It was colonized by Spain for over 300 years starting in 1565, then by the United States after the Spanish-American War of 1898. The country gained full independence in 1946 and is named after King Philip II of Spain.","facts":["An archipelago of over 7,600 islands in Southeast Asia","Named after King Philip II of Spain","Colonized by Spain (1565-1898) then the United States (1898-1946)","Ferdinand Magellan arrived in 1521 and was killed there by chief Lapu-Lapu","Gained full independence from the U.S. on July 4, 1946"]},"Henry VIII":{"desc":"Henry VIII was King of England from 1509 to 1547 and is one of the most famous monarchs in English history. He is best known for having six wives and for breaking away from the Catholic Church to create the Church of England so he could divorce his first wife, Catherine of Aragon. His reign transformed England's religion, politics, and culture forever.","facts":["King of England from 1509 to 1547","Had six wives: Catherine of Aragon, Anne Boleyn, Jane Seymour, Anne of Cleves, Catherine Howard, Catherine Parr","Created the Church of England after the Pope refused to annul his first marriage","Father of Queen Elizabeth I (by Anne Boleyn) and King Edward VI (by Jane Seymour)","Was part of the Tudor dynasty"]},"Mexico City":{"desc":"Mexico City is the capital of Mexico and one of the largest cities in the world. It was built on the ruins of Tenochtitlan, the capital of the Aztec Empire, which was conquered by Spanish conquistador Hernan Cortes in 1521. The city sits in the Valley of Mexico at over 7,000 feet above sea level and has been an important cultural and political center for centuries.","facts":["Built on the ruins of the Aztec capital Tenochtitlan","Conquered by Hernan Cortes and the Spanish in 1521","One of the oldest continuously inhabited cities in the Americas","Sits at over 7,000 feet elevation in the Valley of Mexico","Today it is one of the most populated cities in the world"]},"Martin Luther":{"desc":"Martin Luther was a German monk and professor who started the Protestant Reformation in 1517. He nailed his famous Ninety-Five Theses to the door of a church in Wittenberg, Germany, protesting the Catholic Church's sale of indulgences. His actions split Christianity in Western Europe and led to the creation of Protestant churches.","facts":["Posted his Ninety-Five Theses in Wittenberg in 1517","Protested the Catholic Church's sale of indulgences (paying money for forgiveness of sins)","Was excommunicated by Pope Leo X in 1521","Translated the Bible into German so ordinary people could read it","Started the Protestant Reformation, one of the biggest events in European history"]},"Thomas Jefferson":{"desc":"Thomas Jefferson was the third President of the United States and the primary author of the Declaration of Independence. He served as president from 1801 to 1809 and doubled the size of the country through the Louisiana Purchase in 1803. He was also a skilled architect who designed his home Monticello and founded the University of Virginia.","facts":["Third President of the United States (1801-1809)","Primary author of the Declaration of Independence in 1776","Completed the Louisiana Purchase in 1803, doubling the nation's size","Founded the University of Virginia","Designed his famous home, Monticello, in Virginia"]},"George Washington":{"desc":"George Washington was the first President of the United States, serving from 1789 to 1797. He led the Continental Army to victory against Britain in the American Revolution and is often called the 'Father of His Country.' He set many important precedents, including the tradition of serving only two terms as president.","facts":["First President of the United States (1789-1797)","Commander-in-Chief of the Continental Army during the American Revolution","Presided over the Constitutional Convention in 1787","Famous for crossing the Delaware River on Christmas night 1776","Voluntarily stepped down after two terms, setting a lasting tradition"]},"Watergate scandal":{"desc":"The Watergate scandal was a major political crisis in the United States in the early 1970s. It began when burglars connected to President Richard Nixon's re-election campaign were caught breaking into the Democratic National Committee headquarters at the Watergate hotel complex in Washington, D.C. Nixon's attempts to cover up his involvement led to his resignation on August 9, 1974, making him the only U.S. president to resign from office.","facts":["Burglars broke into the DNC headquarters at the Watergate complex on June 17, 1972","President Nixon tried to cover up his administration's involvement","The scandal was uncovered by Washington Post reporters Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein","Nixon resigned on August 9, 1974 to avoid impeachment","The suffix '-gate' is now used for any major political scandal"]},"Inca Empire":{"desc":"The Inca Empire was the largest empire in pre-Columbian South America, stretching along the western coast from present-day Colombia to Chile. Its capital was Cusco in modern-day Peru. The empire was conquered by Spanish conquistador Francisco Pizarro in 1533, who captured and executed the Inca emperor Atahualpa.","facts":["Largest empire in pre-Columbian Americas, stretching over 2,500 miles","Capital was Cusco in modern-day Peru","Built Machu Picchu, a famous mountain-top city","Used a system of knotted strings called quipu for record-keeping instead of writing","Conquered by Francisco Pizarro and the Spanish in 1533"]},"Trail of Tears":{"desc":"The Trail of Tears refers to the forced relocation of Native American nations from their homelands in the southeastern United States to Indian Territory (present-day Oklahoma) in the 1830s. The Indian Removal Act of 1830, signed by President Andrew Jackson, authorized the government to force these removals. Thousands of Cherokee, Chickasaw, Choctaw, Creek, and Seminole people died from disease, starvation, and exposure during the journey.","facts":["Forced relocation of Native Americans from southeastern U.S. to Oklahoma in the 1830s","Authorized by the Indian Removal Act of 1830 signed by President Andrew Jackson","The Cherokee Nation's removal in 1838 is the most well-known march","Approximately 4,000 Cherokee died during the journey","Five major tribes were relocated: Cherokee, Chickasaw, Choctaw, Creek, and Seminole"]},"Alexander Hamilton":{"desc":"Alexander Hamilton was one of America's Founding Fathers and the first Secretary of the Treasury. He was born in the Caribbean and came to the American colonies as a teenager, eventually becoming George Washington's right-hand man during the Revolution. He created the national banking system and was killed in a famous duel with Vice President Aaron Burr in 1804.","facts":["First Secretary of the Treasury of the United States","Born in the Caribbean island of Nevis","Created the First Bank of the United States and the U.S. financial system","Wrote most of the Federalist Papers defending the Constitution","Killed in a duel by Vice President Aaron Burr on July 11, 1804"]},"Ashoka":{"desc":"Ashoka the Great was an emperor of the Maurya Dynasty in ancient India who ruled from about 268 to 232 BCE. After a bloody conquest of the Kalinga region, he was so horrified by the suffering he caused that he converted to Buddhism and became one of its greatest supporters. He spread Buddhist teachings across Asia and erected stone pillars with moral edicts throughout his empire.","facts":["Emperor of the Maurya Dynasty in ancient India (c. 268-232 BCE)","Conquered the Kalinga region in a very bloody war that killed over 100,000 people","Converted to Buddhism after feeling remorse for the violence he caused","Erected stone pillars with moral edicts throughout his empire","His lion capital pillar is now the national emblem of modern India"]},"Benjamin Franklin":{"desc":"Benjamin Franklin was one of the most famous American Founding Fathers, known as a scientist, inventor, writer, and diplomat. He proved that lightning was electricity with his famous kite experiment and invented the lightning rod, bifocal glasses, and the Franklin stove. He helped draft the Declaration of Independence and secured crucial French support for the American Revolution.","facts":["One of the key Founding Fathers of the United States","Proved lightning was electricity with his famous kite experiment","Invented the lightning rod, bifocal glasses, and the Franklin stove","Served as ambassador to France and helped secure French alliance during the Revolution","His face appears on the U.S. hundred-dollar bill"]},"Harriet Tubman":{"desc":"Harriet Tubman was an escaped enslaved person who became one of the most famous conductors on the Underground Railroad. She made approximately 13 trips back to the South and helped rescue about 70 enslaved people, including her own parents. During the Civil War, she served as a spy and scout for the Union Army, becoming the first woman to lead an armed raid in the war.","facts":["Escaped slavery in Maryland in 1849","Made about 13 trips on the Underground Railroad and rescued about 70 people","Known as 'Moses' for leading people to freedom","Served as a spy and scout for the Union Army during the Civil War","Led the Combahee River Raid in 1863, freeing over 700 enslaved people"]},"Marco Polo":{"desc":"Marco Polo was a Venetian merchant and explorer who traveled from Italy to China along the Silk Road in the 13th century. He spent about 17 years in the court of Kublai Khan, the Mongol emperor of China. His book, 'The Travels of Marco Polo,' introduced Europeans to Central Asia and China and inspired future explorers including Christopher Columbus.","facts":["Venetian merchant who traveled to China in the 13th century","Spent about 17 years at the court of Kublai Khan","Traveled along the Silk Road with his father and uncle","His book 'The Travels of Marco Polo' described the wonders of Asia to Europeans","His accounts inspired Christopher Columbus and other later explorers"]},"Ming dynasty":{"desc":"The Ming dynasty ruled China from 1368 to 1644 and is known for its cultural achievements and powerful centralized government. It was founded by Zhu Yuanzhang, a peasant who overthrew the Mongol-led Yuan dynasty. The Ming dynasty built the Forbidden City in Beijing, expanded the Great Wall of China, and sent Admiral Zheng He on enormous naval voyages across the Indian Ocean.","facts":["Ruled China from 1368 to 1644","Founded by Zhu Yuanzhang (Emperor Hongwu) after overthrowing the Mongol Yuan dynasty","Built the Forbidden City in Beijing as the imperial palace","Expanded and strengthened the Great Wall of China","Admiral Zheng He led massive naval expeditions across the Indian Ocean"]},"Ukraine":{"desc":"In February 2022, Russia invaded Ukraine in the largest military attack in Europe since World War II. The war has caused massive destruction and millions of Ukrainian refugees. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy has led his country's defense and become an internationally recognized figure. The war is still ongoing as of 2026 and has affected global food and energy supplies.","facts":["Ukraine declared independence from the Soviet Union in 1991","Russia had previously annexed Crimea from Ukraine in 2014","Zelenskyy was a comedian and actor before becoming president in 2019","The war disrupted grain exports, since Ukraine is one of the world's largest wheat producers","Many countries imposed economic sanctions on Russia in response to the invasion"]},"Cambodia":{"desc":"Cambodia is a Southeast Asian country known for the ancient Khmer Empire and the temple complex of Angkor Wat. In the 1970s, the Khmer Rouge regime led by Pol Pot carried out a genocide that killed nearly 2 million people. The country has been rebuilding since the regime fell in 1979.","facts":["Home to Angkor Wat, the largest religious monument in the world","The Khmer Empire ruled much of Southeast Asia from the 9th to 15th centuries","The Khmer Rouge under Pol Pot killed nearly 2 million people in the 1970s","Capital city is Phnom Penh"]},"Cyrus the Great":{"desc":"Cyrus the Great founded the Achaemenid Persian Empire in the 6th century BCE, creating the largest empire the world had ever seen at that time. He conquered Babylon in 539 BCE and freed the Jewish people from captivity. He is remembered for his respect for the customs and religions of the people he conquered.","facts":["Founded the Achaemenid (Persian) Empire around 550 BCE","Conquered the Babylonian Empire in 539 BCE","Freed the Jewish people from their Babylonian captivity","Created the Cyrus Cylinder, sometimes called the first declaration of human rights","His empire stretched from modern Turkey to India"]},"Spanish-American War":{"desc":"The Spanish-American War was fought in 1898 between the United States and Spain. The war began after the mysterious sinking of the USS Maine in Havana Harbor and the rallying cry 'Remember the Maine!' The U.S. won quickly, gaining control of Cuba, Puerto Rico, Guam, and the Philippines.","facts":["Fought in 1898 between the U.S. and Spain","Triggered by the sinking of the USS Maine in Havana Harbor","Yellow journalism by Hearst and Pulitzer helped push the U.S. into war","The U.S. gained Puerto Rico, Guam, and the Philippines","Made the U.S. a world power with overseas territories"]},"Alexander the Great":{"desc":"Alexander the Great was king of Macedonia who created one of the largest empires in ancient history by the age of 30. He was tutored by the philosopher Aristotle and never lost a battle. His empire stretched from Greece to northwestern India before he died in Babylon in 323 BCE at just 32 years old.","facts":["King of Macedonia who conquered much of the known world by age 30","Tutored by the philosopher Aristotle as a young man","Never lost a single battle in his military career","His empire stretched from Greece to Egypt to India","Died in Babylon in 323 BCE at age 32"]},"Angkor Wat":{"desc":"Angkor Wat is a massive temple complex in Cambodia and the largest religious monument in the world. It was built in the early 12th century by King Suryavarman II as a Hindu temple dedicated to the god Vishnu, and later became a Buddhist temple. The complex covers over 400 acres.","facts":["Largest religious monument in the world, covering over 400 acres","Built in the early 12th century by King Suryavarman II","Originally a Hindu temple, later converted to Buddhism","Located near Siem Reap, Cambodia","Appears on Cambodia's national flag"]},"North Korea":{"desc":"North Korea, officially the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, was established in 1948 after the Korean Peninsula was divided. It has been ruled by the Kim family dynasty since its founding by Kim Il-sung. The Korean War (1950-1953) was fought when North Korea invaded South Korea, and the two countries remain technically at war today.","facts":["Established in 1948 after the division of the Korean Peninsula","Ruled by the Kim family: Kim Il-sung, Kim Jong-il, and Kim Jong-un","Invaded South Korea in 1950, starting the Korean War","One of the most isolated and secretive countries in the world","The DMZ (Demilitarized Zone) separates North and South Korea"]},"Sparta":{"desc":"Sparta was an ancient Greek city-state known for its powerful military and strict warrior culture. Boys were taken from their families at age 7 to begin military training in a system called the agoge. Sparta's soldiers were famous for their bravery, especially the 300 Spartans who fought at the Battle of Thermopylae against the Persian Empire.","facts":["Ancient Greek city-state famous for its military culture","Boys began military training at age 7 in a system called the agoge","300 Spartans famously defended the pass at Thermopylae against Persia","Fought and won the Peloponnesian War against Athens","Had two kings ruling at the same time"]},"Winston Churchill":{"desc":"Winston Churchill was the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom during most of World War II, from 1940 to 1945. His powerful speeches inspired the British people to keep fighting against Nazi Germany even when things looked hopeless. He won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1953 and is considered one of the greatest wartime leaders in history.","facts":["Prime Minister of the UK during World War II (1940-1945)","Famous for inspiring speeches like 'We shall fight on the beaches'","Led Britain through the Blitz and the war against Nazi Germany","Won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1953","Served as PM again from 1951 to 1955"]},"Aztec Empire":{"desc":"The Aztec Empire was a powerful civilization in central Mexico that flourished from the 14th to 16th centuries. Their capital, Tenochtitlan, was built on an island in Lake Texcoco and was one of the largest cities in the world at the time. The empire was conquered by Spanish conquistador Hernan Cortes in 1521.","facts":["Powerful civilization in central Mexico from the 14th to 16th centuries","Capital Tenochtitlan was built on an island in Lake Texcoco","Practiced human sacrifice as part of their religion","Conquered by Hernan Cortes and the Spanish in 1521","Modern Mexico City is built on the ruins of Tenochtitlan"]},"Forbidden City":{"desc":"The Forbidden City is a massive palace complex in the center of Beijing, China, that served as the home of Chinese emperors for nearly 500 years. It was built during the Ming dynasty between 1406 and 1420 and contains 980 buildings. It is called 'Forbidden' because common people were not allowed to enter.","facts":["Imperial palace in Beijing used for nearly 500 years (1420-1912)","Built during the Ming dynasty between 1406 and 1420","Contains 980 buildings and covers 180 acres","Called 'Forbidden' because commoners could not enter","Now a museum and UNESCO World Heritage Site"]},"Hernan Cortes":{"desc":"Hernan Cortes was a Spanish conquistador who led the expedition that caused the fall of the Aztec Empire in 1521. He landed on the coast of Mexico in 1519 with about 600 men and formed alliances with native peoples who were enemies of the Aztecs. He captured the Aztec emperor Montezuma II and eventually destroyed the capital of Tenochtitlan.","facts":["Spanish conquistador who conquered the Aztec Empire","Landed in Mexico in 1519 with about 600 soldiers","Allied with native groups who opposed the Aztecs","Captured Aztec emperor Montezuma II","Destroyed Tenochtitlan in 1521 and built Mexico City on its ruins"]},"Idi Amin":{"desc":"Idi Amin was a military dictator who ruled Uganda from 1971 to 1979. His regime was known for extreme brutality, with an estimated 100,000 to 500,000 people killed during his rule. He expelled all South Asians from Uganda in 1972 and was finally overthrown when Tanzania invaded in 1979.","facts":["Military dictator of Uganda from 1971 to 1979","Seized power in a military coup against Milton Obote","Between 100,000 and 500,000 people were killed during his rule","Expelled 80,000 South Asians from Uganda in 1972","Overthrown after a war with Tanzania in 1979"]},"March on Washington":{"desc":"The March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom was a massive civil rights demonstration held on August 28, 1963. Over 250,000 people gathered at the Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C., where Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his famous 'I Have a Dream' speech. The march helped lead to the passage of the Civil Rights Act of 1964.","facts":["Held on August 28, 1963 in Washington, D.C.","Over 250,000 people attended the peaceful demonstration","Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his 'I Have a Dream' speech","Organized by civil rights leaders including A. Philip Randolph and Bayard Rustin","Helped lead to the passage of the Civil Rights Act of 1964"]},"Monroe Doctrine":{"desc":"The Monroe Doctrine was a U.S. foreign policy statement made by President James Monroe in 1823. It declared that the Western Hemisphere was closed to further European colonization and that any attempt by European powers to interfere in the Americas would be considered a hostile act. It became a cornerstone of American foreign policy for over a century.","facts":["Announced by President James Monroe in 1823","Warned European powers against further colonization in the Americas","Stated that the U.S. would stay out of European affairs in return","Became a key principle of U.S. foreign policy for over 100 years","Later expanded by Theodore Roosevelt with his 'Roosevelt Corollary'"]},"Monticello":{"desc":"Monticello was the plantation home of Thomas Jefferson, located near Charlottesville, Virginia. Jefferson designed the building himself in a neoclassical style and spent over 40 years building and renovating it. It is now a UNESCO World Heritage Site and a museum dedicated to Jefferson's life and legacy.","facts":["Plantation home of Thomas Jefferson near Charlottesville, Virginia","Designed by Jefferson himself in neoclassical architectural style","Construction and renovation spanned over 40 years","Named from the Italian word for 'little mountain'","Now a UNESCO World Heritage Site and popular museum"]},"Sikhism":{"desc":"Sikhism is a religion founded in the Punjab region of South Asia in the late 15th century by Guru Nanak. It is the world's fifth-largest religion, with over 25 million followers called Sikhs. Sikhs believe in one God, equality of all people, and service to others. Their holy book is called the Guru Granth Sahib.","facts":["Founded by Guru Nanak in the Punjab region in the late 1400s","World's fifth-largest religion with over 25 million followers","Believes in one God, equality, and service to others","The holy book is called the Guru Granth Sahib","The Golden Temple in Amritsar is their holiest site"]},"Tenochtitlan":{"desc":"Tenochtitlan was the capital city of the Aztec Empire, built on an island in Lake Texcoco in the Valley of Mexico. At its height, it had a population of over 200,000 people, making it one of the largest cities in the world. It was conquered and destroyed by Hernan Cortes and the Spanish in 1521, and Mexico City was built on its ruins.","facts":["Capital of the Aztec Empire, built on an island in Lake Texcoco","Population of over 200,000 at its peak","Connected to the mainland by causeways","Had a grand market at Tlatelolco and massive pyramid-temples","Destroyed by Spanish conquistadors in 1521; Mexico City built on its ruins"]},"Battle of New Orleans":{"desc":"The Battle of New Orleans was fought on January 8, 1815, and was the final major battle of the War of 1812. General Andrew Jackson led a diverse force of soldiers, militia, and pirates to a stunning victory over the British. Ironically, a peace treaty had already been signed two weeks earlier, but news traveled slowly in those days.","facts":["Fought on January 8, 1815, the final battle of the War of 1812","Led by General Andrew Jackson against the British","The peace treaty (Treaty of Ghent) had already been signed two weeks before","Made Andrew Jackson a national hero, leading to his presidency","Jackson's force included regulars, militia, free Black soldiers, and pirates"]},"Boston Red Sox":{"desc":"The Boston Red Sox are a Major League Baseball team with a storied history dating back to 1901. They won the first World Series in 1903 but then sold Babe Ruth to the Yankees in 1920, beginning the famous 'Curse of the Bambino' - an 86-year championship drought. They finally broke the curse by winning the 2004 World Series.","facts":["Founded in 1901 as one of the original American League teams","Won the first World Series in 1903","Sold Babe Ruth to the Yankees in 1920, starting the 'Curse of the Bambino'","Did not win another World Series for 86 years until 2004","Play at Fenway Park, the oldest ballpark in Major League Baseball"]},"Brown v. Board of Education":{"desc":"Brown v. Board of Education was a landmark 1954 Supreme Court case that declared racial segregation in public schools unconstitutional. The case was argued by Thurgood Marshall, who later became the first African American Supreme Court justice. The unanimous decision overturned the 'separate but equal' doctrine from the 1896 Plessy v. Ferguson case.","facts":["Landmark 1954 Supreme Court case about school segregation","Declared racial segregation in public schools unconstitutional","Argued by Thurgood Marshall for the NAACP","Overturned the 'separate but equal' ruling from Plessy v. Ferguson (1896)","The unanimous decision was written by Chief Justice Earl Warren"]},"Charlemagne":{"desc":"Charlemagne, also known as Charles the Great, was King of the Franks and the first Holy Roman Emperor. He united much of Western Europe during the early Middle Ages and was crowned Emperor by Pope Leo III on Christmas Day in the year 800. He promoted education and learning in what is called the Carolingian Renaissance.","facts":["King of the Franks who united much of Western Europe","Crowned Emperor by Pope Leo III on Christmas Day, 800 CE","His empire covered modern France, Germany, and parts of Italy and Spain","Promoted education and learning (Carolingian Renaissance)","Often called the 'Father of Europe'"]},"Chile":{"desc":"Chile is a long, narrow country on the western coast of South America, stretching over 2,600 miles from north to south. It gained independence from Spain in 1818 under leaders like Bernardo O'Higgins. In 1973, a military coup led by General Augusto Pinochet overthrew the democratically elected president Salvador Allende.","facts":["Long narrow country on South America's western coast","Gained independence from Spain in 1818","Salvador Allende was the first Marxist president elected in the Americas (1970)","Pinochet's 1973 military coup led to a 17-year dictatorship","The Atacama Desert in northern Chile is the driest place on Earth"]},"Cotton":{"desc":"Cotton was one of the most important crops in American history, especially in the South before the Civil War. The cotton economy was built on the labor of enslaved people, and it made the Southern states extremely wealthy. Cotton was so important to the Southern economy that it was nicknamed 'King Cotton.'","facts":["Most important cash crop in the American South before the Civil War","The cotton economy depended heavily on enslaved labor","Called 'King Cotton' because of its economic dominance","The cotton gin (1793) made cotton production much more profitable","Cotton exports made up most of U.S. foreign trade before the Civil War"]},"Cotton Gin":{"desc":"The cotton gin was invented by Eli Whitney in 1793 and revolutionized cotton production in the American South. The machine quickly separated cotton fibers from seeds, making cotton far more profitable. Ironically, while it made processing easier, it actually increased the demand for enslaved labor because more cotton could be grown and harvested.","facts":["Invented by Eli Whitney in 1793","Separated cotton fibers from seeds much faster than by hand","Made cotton production hugely profitable in the South","Increased demand for enslaved labor rather than reducing it","Helped make cotton the dominant crop of the American South"]},"Czechoslovakia":{"desc":"Czechoslovakia was a country in Central Europe that existed from 1918 to 1993. It was created after World War I from parts of the Austro-Hungarian Empire. Nazi Germany took over part of it in the 1938 Munich Agreement, and after WWII it became a communist state. It peacefully split into the Czech Republic and Slovakia in 1993 in the 'Velvet Divorce.'","facts":["Central European country that existed from 1918 to 1993","Created after World War I from the Austro-Hungarian Empire","The Munich Agreement (1938) gave its Sudetenland region to Nazi Germany","Became communist after World War II","Peacefully split into Czech Republic and Slovakia in 1993 (Velvet Divorce)"]},"Easter Island":{"desc":"Easter Island is a remote island in the southeastern Pacific Ocean, famous for its nearly 1,000 giant stone statues called moai. The island was settled by Polynesian voyagers around 1200 CE. The statues, some weighing over 80 tons, were carved from volcanic rock and represent ancestral figures.","facts":["Remote Pacific island famous for giant stone statues called moai","Settled by Polynesian voyagers around 1200 CE","Nearly 1,000 moai statues carved from volcanic rock","Called 'Rapa Nui' by its native people","Now a territory of Chile and a UNESCO World Heritage Site"]},"Florence":{"desc":"Florence is a city in central Italy that was the birthplace of the Renaissance in the 14th and 15th centuries. The powerful Medici family ruled Florence and supported artists like Leonardo da Vinci, Michelangelo, and Botticelli. The city is home to famous landmarks including the Florence Cathedral with its massive dome designed by Brunelleschi.","facts":["Birthplace of the Renaissance in central Italy","Ruled by the wealthy and powerful Medici family","Home to artists like Leonardo da Vinci, Michelangelo, and Botticelli","The Florence Cathedral dome was designed by Brunelleschi","The Uffizi Gallery houses some of the world's greatest art"]},"Frederick Douglass":{"desc":"Frederick Douglass was an escaped enslaved person who became one of the most powerful voices against slavery in America. He was a brilliant speaker and writer who published his autobiography and a newspaper called The North Star. He advised President Abraham Lincoln during the Civil War and fought for equal rights for African Americans and women.","facts":["Escaped slavery and became a leading abolitionist speaker and writer","Published his autobiography and a newspaper called The North Star","Advised President Lincoln during the Civil War","Fought for both African American rights and women's suffrage","One of the most photographed Americans of the 19th century"]},"French Revolution":{"desc":"The French Revolution began in 1789 when the people of France overthrew the monarchy and demanded liberty, equality, and brotherhood. The revolution included the storming of the Bastille prison and the execution of King Louis XVI and Queen Marie Antoinette by guillotine. It eventually led to the rise of Napoleon Bonaparte.","facts":["Began in 1789 with the storming of the Bastille prison","King Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette were executed by guillotine","The Declaration of the Rights of Man established new principles of freedom","The Reign of Terror (1793-94) led to thousands of executions","Eventually led to the rise of Napoleon Bonaparte"]},"John F. Kennedy":{"desc":"John F. Kennedy (JFK) was the 35th President of the United States, serving from 1961 until his assassination on November 22, 1963 in Dallas, Texas. He was the youngest elected president and led the country during the Cuban Missile Crisis, bringing the world back from the brink of nuclear war. His presidency inspired a generation with his famous call to 'ask not what your country can do for you.'","facts":["35th President of the United States (1961-1963)","Youngest elected president at age 43","Led the nation through the Cuban Missile Crisis in 1962","Assassinated in Dallas, Texas on November 22, 1963","Created the Peace Corps and pushed for the space program"]},"Kansas-Nebraska Act":{"desc":"The Kansas-Nebraska Act was passed by Congress in 1854 and allowed the territories of Kansas and Nebraska to decide for themselves whether to allow slavery through 'popular sovereignty.' The act repealed the Missouri Compromise of 1820 and led to violent conflict known as 'Bleeding Kansas.' It also helped lead to the creation of the Republican Party.","facts":["Passed in 1854, proposed by Senator Stephen Douglas","Allowed Kansas and Nebraska territories to vote on slavery (popular sovereignty)","Repealed the Missouri Compromise of 1820","Led to violent conflict called 'Bleeding Kansas'","Helped create the Republican Party in opposition to slavery's expansion"]},"Leonardo da Vinci":{"desc":"Leonardo da Vinci was an Italian Renaissance genius who excelled as a painter, inventor, scientist, and engineer. He painted the Mona Lisa and The Last Supper, two of the most famous paintings in history. His notebooks contained designs for flying machines, tanks, and other inventions centuries ahead of their time.","facts":["Italian Renaissance artist, scientist, and inventor (1452-1519)","Painted the Mona Lisa and The Last Supper","His notebooks contained designs for flying machines and other futuristic inventions","Called the ultimate 'Renaissance man' for his many talents","Wrote his notes in mirror script (backwards)"]},"Mao Zedong":{"desc":"Mao Zedong was the founding leader of the People's Republic of China, ruling from 1949 until his death in 1976. He led the Chinese Communist Party to victory in the Chinese Civil War. His policies, including the Great Leap Forward and the Cultural Revolution, caused the deaths of tens of millions of people through famine and political persecution.","facts":["Founding leader of the People's Republic of China (1949-1976)","Led the Chinese Communist Party to victory in the Civil War","The Great Leap Forward (1958-62) caused a famine that killed millions","Launched the Cultural Revolution in 1966","His 'Little Red Book' of quotations was distributed throughout China"]},"Nero":{"desc":"Nero was a Roman Emperor who ruled from 54 to 68 CE and is one of the most infamous rulers in history. He is often blamed for starting the Great Fire of Rome in 64 CE, though this is debated by historians. He persecuted early Christians, killed his own mother, and was eventually forced to commit suicide when the Roman Senate turned against him.","facts":["Roman Emperor from 54 to 68 CE","Often blamed for the Great Fire of Rome in 64 CE","Persecuted early Christians after the fire","Killed his mother Agrippina and his wife Octavia","Was the last emperor of the Julio-Claudian dynasty"]},"Peloponnesian War":{"desc":"The Peloponnesian War was a long conflict fought between Athens and Sparta from 431 to 404 BCE. It involved most of the ancient Greek world and ended with Sparta's victory. The war weakened all of Greece and was chronicled by the historian Thucydides, whose account is considered one of the greatest works of history ever written.","facts":["War between Athens and Sparta from 431 to 404 BCE","Ended with Sparta's victory over Athens","Chronicled by the historian Thucydides","Weakened all of Greece, leading to conquest by Macedonia","Pericles led Athens in the early years of the war"]},"Singapore":{"desc":"Singapore is a small island city-state in Southeast Asia that transformed from a colonial trading post into one of the wealthiest nations in the world. Under Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew, who led the country from independence in 1965 until 1990, Singapore became a global financial center with one of the best education systems in the world.","facts":["Small island city-state in Southeast Asia","Gained independence from Malaysia in 1965","Transformed from a poor trading post to a wealthy global financial center","Led by Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew from 1965 to 1990","One of the most prosperous countries in the world today"]},"Tokyo":{"desc":"Tokyo is the capital of Japan and one of the largest metropolitan areas in the world. It was originally a small fishing village called Edo until it became the seat of the Tokugawa shogunate in 1603. The city was almost completely destroyed twice in the 20th century: by the Great Kanto Earthquake of 1923 and by Allied bombing during World War II.","facts":["Capital of Japan, one of the world's largest cities","Originally called Edo, became capital when emperor moved there in 1868","Seat of the Tokugawa shogunate from 1603 to 1868","Devastated by the Great Kanto Earthquake of 1923 and WWII bombing","Hosted the Summer Olympics in 1964 and 2020"]},"USS Maine":{"desc":"The USS Maine was a U.S. Navy battleship that exploded and sank in Havana Harbor, Cuba, on February 15, 1898, killing 266 crew members. The sinking was blamed on Spain, and 'Remember the Maine!' became a rallying cry that helped push the United States into the Spanish-American War. The actual cause of the explosion is still debated today.","facts":["U.S. Navy battleship that sank in Havana Harbor on February 15, 1898","266 crew members were killed in the explosion","'Remember the Maine!' became a rallying cry for war with Spain","Helped trigger the Spanish-American War of 1898","The actual cause of the explosion remains debated"]},"Vikings":{"desc":"The Vikings were Norse seafarers from Scandinavia who explored, traded, and raided across Europe from the 8th to 11th centuries. They were skilled sailors who reached North America around 1000 CE, about 500 years before Columbus. Vikings also settled in Iceland, Greenland, and parts of Britain, France, and Russia.","facts":["Norse seafarers from Scandinavia (Denmark, Norway, Sweden)","Active from about 793 to 1066 CE","Reached North America around 1000 CE at L'Anse aux Meadows","Settled in Iceland, Greenland, Britain, France (Normandy), and Russia","Used longships designed for both ocean voyages and river travel"]},"Vladimir Lenin":{"desc":"Vladimir Lenin was the leader of the Bolshevik Revolution in Russia in 1917 and the first leader of the Soviet Union. He overthrew the Russian government and established a communist state based on the ideas of Karl Marx. He led the Soviet Union until his death in 1924, after which Joseph Stalin took power.","facts":["Leader of the Bolshevik Revolution in October 1917","First leader of the Soviet Union","Established communist government based on Marxist ideas","Led Russia through a brutal civil war (1917-1922)","Died in 1924; succeeded by Joseph Stalin after a power struggle"]},"War of 1812":{"desc":"The War of 1812 was fought between the United States and Great Britain from 1812 to 1815. The war was caused by British interference with American shipping and the impressment of American sailors into the British navy. Key events include the burning of Washington, D.C. by the British and the defense of Fort McHenry, which inspired 'The Star-Spangled Banner.'","facts":["Fought between the U.S. and Britain from 1812 to 1815","Caused by British impressment of American sailors and trade restrictions","The British burned Washington, D.C. including the White House in 1814","The defense of Fort McHenry inspired 'The Star-Spangled Banner'","Ended with the Treaty of Ghent in December 1814"]},"William Howard Taft":{"desc":"William Howard Taft was the 27th President of the United States (1909-1913) and the only person to serve as both President and Chief Justice of the Supreme Court. He was handpicked by Theodore Roosevelt as his successor but the two later became rivals. Taft weighed over 300 pounds and reportedly once got stuck in a White House bathtub.","facts":["27th President of the United States (1909-1913)","Only person to serve as both President and Chief Justice of the Supreme Court","Handpicked by Theodore Roosevelt but later became his rival","Their rivalry split the Republican Party in the 1912 election","Weighed over 300 pounds, the heaviest U.S. president"]},"Witwatersrand gold":{"desc":"The Witwatersrand gold rush began in 1886 when gold was discovered near present-day Johannesburg, South Africa. This discovery led to the rapid growth of Johannesburg and made South Africa the world's largest gold producer. The gold rush also contributed to tensions between the British and the Boer settlers, leading to the Boer Wars.","facts":["Gold discovered near Johannesburg, South Africa in 1886","Made South Africa the world's largest gold producer","Led to the rapid growth of Johannesburg","Contributed to the Boer Wars between British and Dutch settlers","The Witwatersrand basin is the largest gold deposit ever discovered"]},"Abbasid Caliphate":{"desc":"The Abbasid Caliphate was a powerful Islamic empire that ruled much of the Middle East, North Africa, and Central Asia from 750 to 1258 AD. They moved the capital to Baghdad and made it one of the greatest cities in the world, full of scholars, scientists, and artists during a time called the Islamic Golden Age.","facts":["Founded in 750 AD after overthrowing the Umayyad Caliphate","The House of Wisdom in Baghdad was a major center of learning and translation","The Abbasid Caliphate ended when the Mongols destroyed Baghdad in 1258"]},"Abraham Lincoln":{"desc":"Abraham Lincoln was the 16th President of the United States who led the country through the Civil War and ended slavery with the Emancipation Proclamation. He delivered the famous Gettysburg Address and was assassinated by John Wilkes Booth at Ford's Theatre in 1865.","facts":["16th President (1861-1865)","Issued the Emancipation Proclamation in 1863","Delivered the Gettysburg Address","Assassinated by John Wilkes Booth on April 14, 1865","Preserved the Union during the Civil War"]},"Appian Way":{"desc":"The Appian Way was one of the most important roads in ancient Rome, stretching from Rome to the port city of Brindisi in southeastern Italy. Built starting in 312 BC, it was called the 'Queen of Roads' and was so well-built that parts of it are still visible and usable today, over 2,300 years later.","facts":["Construction began in 312 BC under the Roman censor Appius Claudius Caecus","The road stretched about 350 miles (563 km) from Rome to Brindisi on Italy's southeastern coast","After the slave revolt led by Spartacus was defeated in 71 BC, 6,000 captured slaves were crucified along the Appian Way"]},"Archduke Franz Ferdinand":{"desc":"Archduke Franz Ferdinand was the heir to the Austro-Hungarian throne whose assassination on June 28, 1914 in Sarajevo triggered World War I. He was killed by Gavrilo Princip, a Bosnian Serb nationalist, setting off a chain of alliances that plunged Europe into war.","facts":["Heir to the Austro-Hungarian Empire","Assassinated in Sarajevo on June 28, 1914","Killed by Gavrilo Princip","His assassination triggered World War I","The war that followed killed over 17 million people"]},"Atahualpa":{"desc":"Atahualpa was the last emperor of the Inca Empire in South America. He was captured by the Spanish conquistador Francisco Pizarro in 1532 and, despite paying a huge ransom in gold and silver, was executed by the Spanish.","facts":["Atahualpa was captured at the Battle of Cajamarca in November 1532","He offered to fill a room with gold and two rooms with silver as his ransom","He was executed by the Spanish on July 26, 1533"]},"Athens":{"desc":"Athens is the capital of Greece and one of the oldest cities in the world, with a history going back over 3,400 years. In ancient times, Athens was the birthplace of democracy, philosophy, and Western theater, and it produced great thinkers like Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle.","facts":["Athens established the world's first known democracy around 508 BC under the reforms of Cleisthenes","The Golden Age of Athens under Pericles (roughly 461-429 BC) saw the construction of the Parthenon and great advances in art and philosophy","Athens and Sparta fought the Peloponnesian War from 431 to 404 BC, which Athens eventually lost"]},"Attila the Hun":{"desc":"Attila the Hun was the fearsome leader of the Hunnic Empire who terrorized both the Roman Empire and much of Europe in the 5th century AD. He was so feared that he was nicknamed the 'Scourge of God,' and his armies invaded and plundered lands from modern-day Germany to Greece.","facts":["He ruled the Hunnic Empire from 434 to 453 AD, sharing power with his brother Bleda until he had him killed around 445","He invaded Gaul (modern France) in 451 and was defeated at the Battle of the Catalaunian Plains by a Roman-Visigothic alliance","He died in 453 AD on his wedding night, reportedly from a severe nosebleed, and his empire quickly fell apart after his death"]},"Baghdad":{"desc":"Baghdad is the capital of modern-day Iraq and was once the largest and most advanced city in the world. It was founded in 762 AD by the Abbasid Caliph al-Mansur and became a center of learning, trade, and culture during the Islamic Golden Age.","facts":["Founded in 762 AD as a perfectly round city called the 'Round City' or Madinat al-Salam","At its peak around 900 AD, Baghdad had a population of over one million people","The Mongol siege of 1258 destroyed much of the city and killed hundreds of thousands"]},"Baikonur Cosmodrome":{"desc":"The Baikonur Cosmodrome is the world's oldest and largest space launch facility, located in Kazakhstan. It was built by the Soviet Union in the 1950s and is where many of history's most famous space missions launched from.","facts":["Sputnik, the first artificial satellite, launched from Baikonur on October 4, 1957","Yuri Gagarin launched from Baikonur on April 12, 1961, becoming the first human in space","Russia still leases the site from Kazakhstan and uses it for crewed missions to the International Space Station"]},"Barack Obama":{"desc":"Barack Obama was the 44th President of the United States and the first African American to hold the office. He served two terms from 2009 to 2017 and is known for the Affordable Care Act and ordering the mission that found Osama bin Laden.","facts":["Born on August 4, 1961, in Honolulu, Hawaii","He was a U.S. Senator from Illinois before becoming president","He received the Nobel Peace Prize in 2009"]},"Battle of Antietam":{"desc":"The Battle of Antietam was fought on September 17, 1862, near Sharpsburg, Maryland, and remains the single bloodiest day in American military history with about 23,000 casualties. Though tactically a draw, it was enough of a Union success that President Lincoln used it as the occasion to announce the Emancipation Proclamation.","facts":["Fought September 17, 1862 - bloodiest single day in American history","About 23,000 soldiers were killed, wounded, or missing","Fought near Sharpsburg, Maryland at Antietam Creek","Gave Lincoln the opportunity to announce the Emancipation Proclamation","Stopped Confederate General Lee's first invasion of the North"]},"Battle of Borodino":{"desc":"The Battle of Borodino was a huge battle fought on September 7, 1812, between Napoleon's French army and the Russian army near Moscow. It was one of the bloodiest single-day battles in history, and even though Napoleon technically won, the Russians were not truly defeated and kept fighting.","facts":["Fought on September 7, 1812, about 75 miles west of Moscow","Around 70,000 soldiers were killed or wounded in a single day","Russian general Mikhail Kutuzov commanded the Russian forces against Napoleon"]},"Battle of Gettysburg":{"desc":"The Battle of Gettysburg was fought from July 1-3, 1863 in Pennsylvania and was the bloodiest battle of the American Civil War. The Union victory was a major turning point, ending Confederate General Robert E. Lee's invasion of the North. President Lincoln later gave the Gettysburg Address at the battlefield cemetery.","facts":["Fought July 1-3, 1863 in Gettysburg, Pennsylvania","Bloodiest battle of the Civil War with about 50,000 casualties","Major turning point - ended Lee's invasion of the North","Pickett's Charge on the third day was a disastrous Confederate attack","Lincoln delivered the Gettysburg Address at the battlefield cemetery"]},"Battle of the Bulge":{"desc":"The Battle of the Bulge was the last major German offensive on the Western Front during World War II, fought from December 1944 to January 1945 in the forested Ardennes region of Belgium. It was the largest and bloodiest battle fought by the United States in WWII.","facts":["Last major German offensive in WWII (December 1944 - January 1945)","Fought in the Ardennes forest region of Belgium","Germans created a 'bulge' in Allied lines, giving the battle its name","Largest battle fought by U.S. forces in World War II","Allied victory helped end the war in Europe"]},"Benjamin Henry Latrobe":{"desc":"Benjamin Henry Latrobe was a British-American architect who is often called the father of American architecture. He designed important buildings in the early United States, including parts of the U.S. Capitol building in Washington, D.C.","facts":["He designed the Baltimore Basilica, the first Roman Catholic cathedral in the United States","He helped rebuild the U.S. Capitol after the British burned it in 1814","He was born in England in 1764 and moved to the United States in 1796"]},"Brazil":{"desc":"Brazil is the largest country in South America and was colonized by Portugal beginning in 1500. It gained independence in 1822 when Pedro I declared himself emperor. Brazil was the last country in the Western Hemisphere to abolish slavery in 1888.","facts":["Largest country in South America","Colonized by Portugal starting in 1500","Gained independence in 1822 under Emperor Pedro I","Last country in the Western Hemisphere to abolish slavery (1888)","Capital moved from Rio de Janeiro to the new city of Brasilia in 1960"]},"Buddhism":{"desc":"Buddhism is one of the world's major religions, founded by Siddhartha Gautama (the Buddha) in India around 500 BC. The Buddha taught that people could end suffering by following the Eightfold Path, which includes being kind, thinking clearly, and meditating.","facts":["Siddhartha Gautama, the founder, was born around 563 BC in what is now Nepal","The Four Noble Truths are the core teachings of Buddhism about suffering and how to end it","Buddhism spread from India to China, Japan, Southeast Asia, and eventually the whole world"]},"Congress of Vienna":{"desc":"The Congress of Vienna was a meeting of European powers in 1814-1815 to reorganize Europe after the defeat of Napoleon. Led by Austrian diplomat Klemens von Metternich, it redrew the map of Europe and established a balance of power that kept relative peace for nearly a century.","facts":["Held in 1814-1815 after Napoleon's defeat","Led by Austrian diplomat Klemens von Metternich","Redrew the borders of Europe","Established a balance of power among major nations","Created a period of relative peace in Europe lasting until World War I"]},"Constantine the Great":{"desc":"Constantine I, known as Constantine the Great, was a Roman Emperor who ruled from 306 to 337 CE. He was the first Roman emperor to convert to Christianity and issued the Edict of Milan in 313 CE, which legalized Christianity throughout the empire. He also founded Constantinople as the new eastern capital.","facts":["Roman Emperor from 306 to 337 CE","First Roman emperor to convert to Christianity","Issued the Edict of Milan (313 CE) legalizing Christianity","Founded Constantinople as the new eastern capital","Presided over the Council of Nicaea in 325 CE"]},"Cuba":{"desc":"Cuba is the largest island in the Caribbean, located just 90 miles south of Florida. Fidel Castro led a communist revolution in 1959 that overthrew dictator Fulgencio Batista. Cuba's communist government and its close ties to the Soviet Union made it a key flashpoint during the Cold War, especially during the Cuban Missile Crisis.","facts":["Largest island in the Caribbean","Fidel Castro led a communist revolution in 1959","Located just 90 miles from Florida","Center of the 1962 Cuban Missile Crisis","U.S. imposed an economic embargo that lasted for decades"]},"Cuban Missile Crisis":{"desc":"The Cuban Missile Crisis of October 1962 was a 13-day confrontation between the United States and Soviet Union that brought the world to the brink of nuclear war. President Kennedy discovered the Soviets were placing nuclear missiles in Cuba and demanded their removal. The crisis ended when the Soviets agreed to remove the missiles.","facts":["Occurred in October 1962 over 13 tense days","Soviet Union placed nuclear missiles in Cuba","President Kennedy ordered a naval blockade of Cuba","Closest the world came to nuclear war during the Cold War","Resolved when Soviets removed missiles; U.S. secretly removed missiles from Turkey"]},"Delaware":{"desc":"Delaware is known as 'The First State' because it was the first state to ratify the U.S. Constitution on December 7, 1787. It is the second-smallest state by area and is located on the East Coast between Maryland and New Jersey.","facts":["Its capital is Dover","Delaware was one of the original 13 colonies, first settled by the Dutch and Swedes","It is the sixth-least populous U.S. state"]},"Federalist Party":{"desc":"The Federalist Party was one of the first political parties in the United States, founded in the early 1790s. Led by Alexander Hamilton and John Adams, they supported a strong national government and a national bank.","facts":["John Adams was the only Federalist president, serving from 1797 to 1801","Alexander Hamilton was the party's main founder and organizer","The party faded away after the War of 1812 and was mostly gone by the 1820s"]},"Frederick Law Olmsted":{"desc":"Frederick Law Olmsted was a famous American landscape architect who is often called the father of American landscape architecture. He is best known for designing Central Park in New York City along with his partner Calvert Vaux.","facts":["He was born on April 26, 1822, in Hartford, Connecticut","He also designed Prospect Park in Brooklyn and the grounds of the U.S. Capitol","He helped create the plan to preserve Yosemite Valley and was involved in establishing national parks"]},"Frederick the Great":{"desc":"Frederick the Great was the King of Prussia from 1740 to 1786 and one of the most famous rulers in European history. He was a brilliant military leader who made Prussia into a major European power, but he also loved music, philosophy, and the arts.","facts":["He ruled Prussia for 46 years, from 1740 until his death in 1786","He played the flute and even composed over 100 pieces of music","He fought in the Seven Years' War (1756–1763) against a coalition of Austria, France, and Russia"]},"Genghis Khan":{"desc":"Genghis Khan founded the Mongol Empire in 1206, which became the largest contiguous land empire in history. Born as Temujin, he united the Mongol tribes and conquered vast territories across Asia and into Europe. His empire stretched from China to Eastern Europe.","facts":["Founded the Mongol Empire in 1206","Born as Temujin and united Mongol tribes","Created the largest contiguous land empire in history","Established a legal code called the Yasa","His descendants continued expanding the empire after his death in 1227"]},"Glorious Revolution":{"desc":"The Glorious Revolution happened in 1688 when the English Parliament invited William of Orange from the Netherlands to replace King James II. It was called 'glorious' because the change of power happened mostly without bloodshed and led to more power for Parliament over the king.","facts":["It took place in 1688–1689 in England","King James II fled to France after William of Orange arrived with his army","It led to the English Bill of Rights in 1689, which limited the power of the monarchy"]},"Great Depression":{"desc":"The Great Depression was the worst economic downturn in modern history, lasting from 1929 to the late 1930s. It began with the stock market crash of October 1929 and led to massive unemployment, poverty, and hardship worldwide. President Franklin D. Roosevelt's New Deal programs helped America begin to recover.","facts":["Began with the stock market crash of October 29, 1929 (Black Tuesday)","Unemployment in the U.S. reached about 25%","Affected countries around the world","FDR's New Deal created jobs and social programs","Fully ended only with the industrial production of World War II"]},"Haiti":{"desc":"Haiti occupies the western third of the island of Hispaniola in the Caribbean. In 1804, it became the first Black republic and the second independent nation in the Western Hemisphere after a successful slave revolt led by Toussaint Louverture and Jean-Jacques Dessalines against the French.","facts":["First Black republic, independent since 1804","Successful slave revolt against French colonial rule","Led by Toussaint Louverture and Jean-Jacques Dessalines","Second independent nation in the Western Hemisphere after the U.S.","Occupies the western third of Hispaniola"]},"Holy Roman Empire":{"desc":"The Holy Roman Empire was a complex political entity in Central Europe that lasted from 962 to 1806. It was famously described by Voltaire as 'neither holy, nor Roman, nor an empire.' At its height it covered modern Germany, Austria, Czech Republic, and parts of Italy and France.","facts":["Existed from 962 to 1806 in Central Europe","Voltaire said it was 'neither holy, nor Roman, nor an empire'","Charlemagne is considered its founder","Covered modern Germany, Austria, and surrounding areas","Dissolved by Napoleon in 1806"]},"I Have a Dream":{"desc":"\"I Have a Dream\" is the famous title of a speech delivered by Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. during the March on Washington in 1963. The phrase became a powerful symbol of the civil rights movement and the hope for racial equality in America.","facts":["The speech was given on August 28, 1963, at the Lincoln Memorial","About 250,000 people attended the March on Washington that day","The phrase 'I have a dream' was partly improvised — King departed from his written notes"]},"I Have a Dream speech":{"desc":"The I Have a Dream speech was delivered by Martin Luther King Jr. on the steps of the Lincoln Memorial during the March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom. It is considered one of the greatest speeches in American history and called for an end to racism and for civil and economic rights.","facts":["The speech lasted about 17 minutes","Gospel singer Mahalia Jackson shouted 'Tell them about the dream, Martin!' which prompted King to improvise","The speech helped lead to the passage of the Civil Rights Act of 1964"]},"Indira Gandhi":{"desc":"Indira Gandhi was the first female Prime Minister of India, serving from 1966 to 1977 and again from 1980 to 1984. She was the daughter of India's first Prime Minister, Jawaharlal Nehru. She was assassinated by her own Sikh bodyguards in 1984 after she ordered a military attack on the Golden Temple in Amritsar.","facts":["First female Prime Minister of India","Daughter of Jawaharlal Nehru, India's first Prime Minister","Declared a state of emergency from 1975 to 1977","Ordered Operation Blue Star, a military assault on the Golden Temple","Assassinated by her Sikh bodyguards on October 31, 1984"]},"Iran Hostage Crisis":{"desc":"The Iran Hostage Crisis began on November 4, 1979, when Iranian students stormed the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and held 52 American diplomats and citizens hostage. The crisis lasted 444 days and was a major event during President Jimmy Carter's time in office.","facts":["The hostages were released on January 20, 1981, the same day Ronald Reagan was inaugurated as president","A rescue attempt called Operation Eagle Claw failed in April 1980","The crisis was triggered partly by the U.S. allowing the deposed Shah of Iran to enter America for medical treatment"]},"Isaac Newton":{"desc":"Isaac Newton was an English scientist born in 1642 who changed the way people understand the world through his discoveries about gravity, light, and motion. He is often considered one of the most important scientists who ever lived, and his ideas helped launch the Scientific Revolution.","facts":["He published his most famous book, Principia Mathematica, in 1687","He discovered that white light is actually made up of a spectrum of colors","He was born on December 25, 1642, in Woolsthorpe, Lincolnshire, England"]},"John Brown":{"desc":"John Brown was an abolitionist who believed that armed rebellion was the only way to end slavery in the United States. He led a famous raid on the federal armory at Harpers Ferry, Virginia, in 1859, hoping to start a slave uprising.","facts":["He was captured by a force led by Colonel Robert E. Lee at Harpers Ferry","He was tried and hanged on December 2, 1859","In 1856, he and his followers killed five pro-slavery settlers in the Pottawatomie Massacre in Kansas"]},"John Marshall":{"desc":"John Marshall was the fourth Chief Justice of the United States and served for 34 years, from 1801 to 1835, making him the longest-serving Chief Justice. He is famous for establishing the power of judicial review, which lets the Supreme Court decide if laws are constitutional.","facts":["He established judicial review in the landmark case Marbury v. Madison in 1803","He was appointed by President John Adams","He served in the Continental Army during the American Revolution before becoming a lawyer"]},"Joseph Stalin":{"desc":"Joseph Stalin was the dictator of the Soviet Union from the mid-1920s until his death in 1953. He transformed the USSR into an industrial power but at enormous human cost, including forced collectivization, political purges, and the gulag labor camp system.","facts":["Ruled the Soviet Union from the mid-1920s to 1953","Forced collectivization caused massive famine in Ukraine (Holodomor)","The Great Purge eliminated political opponents","Led the Soviet Union during World War II","His policies killed millions of people"]},"Kublai Khan":{"desc":"Kublai Khan was the grandson of Genghis Khan who became the ruler of the Mongol Empire and founded the Yuan Dynasty in China. He was the first non-Chinese person to conquer and rule all of China, and he welcomed visitors from far-away lands, including the famous explorer Marco Polo.","facts":["He established the Yuan Dynasty in 1271 and ruled China until his death in 1294","He tried to invade Japan twice, in 1274 and 1281, but both attempts failed partly due to typhoons called 'kamikaze'","Marco Polo claimed to have served in Kublai Khan's court for about 17 years"]},"Lebanon":{"desc":"Lebanon is a small country on the eastern coast of the Mediterranean Sea with a very long history going back thousands of years. The ancient Phoenicians, who lived in what is now Lebanon, were famous sailors and traders who invented one of the first alphabets that many modern alphabets are based on.","facts":["The ancient city of Byblos in Lebanon is one of the oldest continuously inhabited cities in the world, dating back over 7,000 years","A devastating civil war lasted from 1975 to 1990, involving many different religious and political groups","The cedar tree on Lebanon's flag represents the famous Cedars of Lebanon mentioned in the Bible"]},"Lee Kuan Yew":{"desc":"Lee Kuan Yew was the first Prime Minister of Singapore, serving from 1959 to 1990. He transformed Singapore from a tiny, poor island with no natural resources into one of the wealthiest and most modern countries in the world.","facts":["He served as Prime Minister for 31 years, making him one of the longest-serving leaders in history","Singapore was expelled from Malaysia in 1965, and Lee Kuan Yew cried on television when announcing independence","Under his leadership, Singapore's GDP per capita grew from about $500 in 1965 to over $12,000 by 1990"]},"Missouri Compromise":{"desc":"The Missouri Compromise was a law passed in 1820 that tried to keep the balance between free states and slave states in the United States. It admitted Missouri as a slave state and Maine as a free state, and banned slavery in the rest of the Louisiana Territory north of the 36°30' line.","facts":["It was proposed by Senator Henry Clay of Kentucky","The compromise was struck down by the Supreme Court in the Dred Scott decision of 1857","It kept the number of free and slave states equal at 12 each at the time"]},"Montgomery Alabama":{"desc":"Montgomery, Alabama, played a key role in both the Civil War and the civil rights movement. It served as the first capital of the Confederate States of America in 1861 and was the city where Rosa Parks refused to give up her bus seat in 1955, sparking the Montgomery Bus Boycott.","facts":["The Montgomery Bus Boycott lasted 381 days, from December 1955 to December 1956","Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. was the leader of the boycott and was pastor of Dexter Avenue Baptist Church in Montgomery","Jefferson Davis was inaugurated as president of the Confederacy on the steps of the Alabama State Capitol in Montgomery on February 18, 1861"]},"Mother Teresa":{"desc":"Mother Teresa was a Catholic nun who spent most of her life helping the poorest people in Calcutta, India. She founded the Missionaries of Charity and became one of the most recognized humanitarian figures in the world.","facts":["She was born on August 26, 1910, in Skopje, which is now the capital of North Macedonia","She won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1979","She was declared a saint by Pope Francis on September 4, 2016"]},"Muhammad":{"desc":"Muhammad was the founder of Islam and is considered by Muslims to be the last prophet sent by God. He was born around 570 AD in the city of Mecca in what is now Saudi Arabia, and his teachings became the basis for one of the world's largest religions, with nearly two billion followers today.","facts":["Muslims believe he received revelations from God starting in 610 AD, which were written down as the Quran","In 622 AD, he migrated from Mecca to Medina in an event called the Hijra, which marks the start of the Islamic calendar","By the time of his death in 632 AD, most of the Arabian Peninsula had united under Islam"]},"NATO":{"desc":"NATO (North Atlantic Treaty Organization) is a military alliance formed in 1949 by the United States, Canada, and several Western European nations. It was created to counter the threat of Soviet expansion during the Cold War. The key principle is collective defense: an attack on one member is considered an attack on all.","facts":["Military alliance formed in 1949","Created to counter Soviet expansion during the Cold War","Based on collective defense - attack on one is attack on all (Article 5)","Originally 12 members, now over 30","The Soviet response was to create the Warsaw Pact in 1955"]},"New York Times":{"desc":"The New York Times is one of the most famous and respected newspapers in the United States, first published on September 18, 1851. Often called 'The Gray Lady,' it has won more Pulitzer Prizes than any other newspaper.","facts":["It was founded by Henry Jarvis Raymond and George Jones in 1851","The paper published the Pentagon Papers in 1971, revealing secret information about the Vietnam War","It has won over 130 Pulitzer Prizes, more than any other news organization"]},"Nile River":{"desc":"The Nile River is the longest river in Africa, flowing over 4,000 miles through northeastern Africa to the Mediterranean Sea. Ancient Egyptian civilization depended entirely on the Nile's annual floods, which deposited rich soil for farming. The river was so important that the Greek historian Herodotus called Egypt 'the gift of the Nile.'","facts":["Longest river in Africa at over 4,000 miles","Ancient Egyptian civilization depended on its annual floods","Herodotus called Egypt 'the gift of the Nile'","Flows northward through eleven countries","The Aswan Dam now controls the river's flooding"]},"Oliver Cromwell":{"desc":"Oliver Cromwell was an English military and political leader who helped overthrow King Charles I during the English Civil War. After the king was executed in 1649, Cromwell ruled England as Lord Protector until his death in 1658, making him the only non-royal to lead England in modern history.","facts":["He signed the death warrant of King Charles I, who was beheaded on January 30, 1649","He served as Lord Protector of England from 1653 to 1658","After the monarchy was restored, his body was dug up and symbolically executed in 1661"]},"Oracle of Delphi":{"desc":"The Oracle of Delphi was the most important religious site in ancient Greece, where a priestess called the Pythia gave prophecies believed to come from the god Apollo. Kings, generals, and ordinary people traveled from all over the ancient world to ask the Oracle for advice on important decisions.","facts":["The Oracle was located at the Temple of Apollo on the slopes of Mount Parnassus in central Greece","The Pythia sat on a tripod over a crack in the earth and inhaled vapors that scientists now believe may have been ethylene gas","The Oracle was active for nearly 1,000 years, from about the 8th century BC until it was closed by the Roman Emperor Theodosius I in 393 AD"]},"Osiris":{"desc":"Osiris was one of the most important gods in ancient Egyptian mythology, known as the god of the afterlife, death, and resurrection. According to myth, he was murdered by his jealous brother Set, but was brought back to life by his wife Isis, becoming the ruler of the underworld.","facts":["Set tricked Osiris into lying in a coffin, sealed it shut, and threw it into the Nile River to kill him","His wife Isis reassembled his body after Set cut it into pieces and scattered them across Egypt","Ancient Egyptians believed that Osiris judged the souls of the dead by weighing their hearts against the feather of Ma'at (truth)"]},"Pentagon":{"desc":"The Pentagon is the headquarters of the United States Department of Defense, located in Arlington, Virginia. It is one of the world's largest office buildings and was built during World War II.","facts":["Construction began on September 11, 1941, and it was completed on January 15, 1943","It has five sides, five floors above ground, and about 17.5 miles of corridors","On September 11, 2001, a hijacked plane crashed into the Pentagon, killing 189 people"]},"Persian Empire":{"desc":"The Persian Empire, also known as the Achaemenid Empire, was founded by Cyrus the Great around 550 BCE and became the largest empire the ancient world had seen. It stretched from modern Turkey and Egypt to India and was known for its tolerance of different cultures and religions.","facts":["Founded by Cyrus the Great around 550 BCE","Largest empire of the ancient world","Stretched from Egypt to India","Known for tolerance of conquered peoples' cultures","Defeated by Alexander the Great in 330 BCE"]},"Plato":{"desc":"Plato was an ancient Greek philosopher who lived from about 428 to 348 BCE and was a student of Socrates. He founded the Academy in Athens, one of the first institutions of higher learning in the Western world. His writings, including The Republic, explored justice, beauty, equality, and the ideal form of government.","facts":["Ancient Greek philosopher (c. 428-348 BCE)","Student of Socrates and teacher of Aristotle","Founded the Academy in Athens","Wrote The Republic about justice and ideal government","Developed the Theory of Forms about ideal versions of things"]},"Qin Shi Huang":{"desc":"Qin Shi Huang was the first emperor to unify all of China in 221 BCE, founding the Qin dynasty. He standardized weights, measures, and writing across China, and began construction of the Great Wall. He is also famous for his massive tomb guarded by thousands of terracotta warrior statues.","facts":["First Emperor of unified China in 221 BCE","Standardized weights, measures, currency, and writing","Began construction of the Great Wall of China","His tomb is guarded by the famous Terracotta Army","The name 'China' may come from 'Qin' (pronounced 'Chin')"]},"Qing Dynasty":{"desc":"The Qing Dynasty was the last imperial dynasty of China, ruling from 1644 to 1912. It was founded by the Manchus, a people from northeastern China, and at its largest it controlled a huge territory including China, Mongolia, Tibet, and parts of Central Asia.","facts":["The Qing Dynasty required Chinese men to wear their hair in a long braid called a queue as a sign of loyalty","Emperor Kangxi ruled for 61 years (1661-1722), one of the longest reigns in Chinese history","The dynasty ended when the last emperor, six-year-old Puyi, was forced to abdicate in 1912"]},"Rosa Parks":{"desc":"Rosa Parks was a civil rights activist who refused to give up her bus seat to a white passenger in Montgomery, Alabama on December 1, 1955. Her arrest sparked the Montgomery Bus Boycott, a key event in the civil rights movement led by Martin Luther King Jr.","facts":["Refused to give up her bus seat on December 1, 1955","Her arrest sparked the Montgomery Bus Boycott","The boycott lasted 381 days","Known as the 'Mother of the Civil Rights Movement'","The Supreme Court ruled bus segregation unconstitutional in 1956"]},"Sabines":{"desc":"The Sabines were an ancient Italian people who lived in the hills northeast of Rome and played an important role in Rome's early history. According to Roman legend, the first Romans kidnapped Sabine women to be their wives in an event called the 'Rape of the Sabine Women,' which led to war and eventually peace between the two peoples.","facts":["The legendary 'Rape of the Sabine Women' (meaning 'seizure') was said to have happened during the reign of Rome's founder, Romulus","After the Sabine women intervened to stop the war between their fathers and husbands, the Romans and Sabines merged into one community","The Sabine king Titus Tatius co-ruled Rome with Romulus after the two peoples united"]},"Salt March":{"desc":"The Salt March was a famous act of nonviolent protest led by Mahatma Gandhi in 1930 against British rule in India. Gandhi and his followers walked 240 miles to the sea to make their own salt, breaking the British law that said only the British government could make and sell salt.","facts":["The march began on March 12, 1930, from Gandhi's ashram in Sabarmati and ended at the coastal village of Dandi on April 6","Gandhi started with 78 followers, but thousands joined along the 24-day, 240-mile journey","About 60,000 people were arrested for making or selling salt illegally during the protests that followed"]},"Sir Isaac Newton":{"desc":"Sir Isaac Newton was knighted by Queen Anne in 1705, making him one of the first scientists to receive such an honor. Beyond his famous work on gravity and motion, he also served as Warden and then Master of the Royal Mint, helping to reform England's currency system.","facts":["He was knighted by Queen Anne in 1705 at Trinity College, Cambridge","He served as president of the Royal Society from 1703 until his death in 1727","He spent nearly 30 years as Master of the Royal Mint, fighting counterfeiters"]},"Song Dynasty":{"desc":"The Song Dynasty ruled China from 960 to 1279 AD and was a time of amazing inventions and advances in art, science, and technology. During this period, China was the most advanced civilization in the world, with more people and bigger cities than anywhere in Europe.","facts":["The Song Dynasty saw the invention of gunpowder weapons, the magnetic compass for navigation, and movable-type printing","The capital city of Kaifeng had a population of over one million people by the year 1000","The dynasty is divided into Northern Song (960-1127) and Southern Song (1127-1279) after losing northern territory to the Jurchen Jin Dynasty"]},"Spanish Civil War":{"desc":"The Spanish Civil War was fought from 1936 to 1939 between the Republican government of Spain and a group of rebel military officers led by General Francisco Franco. Franco's side won and he became the dictator of Spain, ruling the country until his death in 1975.","facts":["The war lasted from July 1936 to April 1939","Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy sent troops and weapons to help Franco's side","The famous painting Guernica by Pablo Picasso was inspired by the bombing of a Spanish town during this war"]},"Spartacus":{"desc":"Spartacus was a gladiator and former slave who led the biggest slave revolt in Roman history, known as the Third Servile War, from 73 to 71 BC. He escaped from a gladiator training school with about 70 other gladiators and eventually led an army of around 70,000 escaped slaves against Rome.","facts":["He escaped from a gladiator school in Capua in 73 BC with about 70 other gladiators armed with kitchen knives","His rebel army grew to an estimated 70,000 to 120,000 escaped slaves and defeated several Roman armies","He was defeated by the Roman general Marcus Licinius Crassus in 71 BC, and 6,000 captured rebels were crucified along the Appian Way"]},"Squanto":{"desc":"Squanto, also known as Tisquantum, was a Patuxet Native American who helped the Pilgrims survive after they arrived at Plymouth Colony in 1620. He taught them how to grow corn, catch fish, and find their way around the area.","facts":["He had learned English after being captured and taken to Europe before returning to America","He served as an interpreter between the Pilgrims and the Wampanoag chief Massasoit","He died in November 1622 of a fever while guiding a trading expedition"]},"Sri Lanka":{"desc":"Sri Lanka is an island country located just south of India in the Indian Ocean. It has a long history going back over 2,500 years, with ancient kingdoms that built impressive cities, temples, and irrigation systems that still amaze people today.","facts":["The ancient city of Anuradhapura served as the capital for over 1,000 years, from the 4th century BC to the 11th century AD","A civil war between the government and the Tamil Tigers lasted from 1983 to 2009","The Portuguese arrived in 1505, followed by the Dutch and then the British, who controlled the island until independence in 1948"]},"St. Louis":{"desc":"St. Louis, Missouri, was an important city in American westward expansion and is known as the 'Gateway to the West.' It was the starting point for explorers like Lewis and Clark and later became a major center for trade and transportation on the Mississippi River.","facts":["The city was founded in 1764 by French fur traders Pierre Laclède and Auguste Chouteau","The Gateway Arch, completed in 1965, stands 630 feet tall and is the tallest man-made monument in the United States","St. Louis hosted the 1904 World's Fair and the 1904 Summer Olympics"]},"St. Petersburg":{"desc":"St. Petersburg is a beautiful city in Russia that was founded by Tsar Peter the Great in 1703. It served as the capital of the Russian Empire for over 200 years and is famous for its grand palaces, museums, and canals.","facts":["Founded by Peter the Great on May 27, 1703","The city was renamed Petrograd in 1914 and Leningrad in 1924, then changed back to St. Petersburg in 1991","The Hermitage Museum in St. Petersburg is one of the largest art museums in the world with over 3 million items"]},"Tecumseh":{"desc":"Tecumseh was a Shawnee chief who tried to unite Native American tribes into a large confederation to resist American expansion into their lands. He was one of the most important Native American leaders in American history.","facts":["He was born around 1768 in present-day Ohio","He was killed at the Battle of the Thames in Ontario, Canada, on October 5, 1813, while fighting alongside the British in the War of 1812","His brother Tenskwatawa, known as 'The Prophet,' helped him build the confederacy through a religious movement"]},"Vienna":{"desc":"Vienna is the capital city of Austria and was once the center of the powerful Habsburg Empire that ruled much of Europe for centuries. It is famous for its beautiful architecture, classical music heritage, and for being the home of composers like Mozart, Beethoven, and Strauss.","facts":["Vienna was the capital of the Habsburg Empire for over 600 years","The Congress of Vienna in 1814–1815 redrew the map of Europe after Napoleon's defeat","Composers Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, Ludwig van Beethoven, and Johann Strauss II all lived and worked in Vienna"]},"Warsaw":{"desc":"Warsaw is the capital city of Poland and has a long and dramatic history, including being almost completely destroyed during World War II. After the war, the Polish people rebuilt the city's historic Old Town brick by brick, and today it is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.","facts":["About 85% of Warsaw was destroyed during World War II","The Warsaw Uprising of 1944 was a major revolt by Polish resistance fighters against Nazi German occupation","The Warsaw Pact, a military alliance of Eastern European communist countries, was named after the city and signed there in 1955"]},"Washington Crossing the Delaware":{"desc":"On the night of December 25-26, 1776, General George Washington led about 2,400 Continental Army soldiers across the icy Delaware River to launch a surprise attack on Hessian troops at Trenton, New Jersey. This bold move was a turning point in the American Revolution when things looked very bad for the Continental Army.","facts":["The attack resulted in the capture of about 1,000 Hessian soldiers","The famous painting of the event was created by Emanuel Leutze in 1851","Washington's army crossed the river in Durham boats during a snowstorm"]},"West Point":{"desc":"West Point is the United States Military Academy located in West Point, New York, and is one of the most famous military schools in the world. It has trained many important American military leaders and has been in operation since 1802.","facts":["It was established on March 16, 1802, by President Thomas Jefferson","Famous graduates include Ulysses S. Grant, Robert E. Lee, and Dwight D. Eisenhower","During the American Revolution, Benedict Arnold tried to hand over the fort at West Point to the British"]},"Zionism":{"desc":"Zionism is a movement that began in the late 1800s to create a homeland for Jewish people in the land of Israel. It led to the founding of the modern State of Israel in 1948, giving Jewish people their own country after centuries without one.","facts":["Theodor Herzl is considered the father of modern Zionism after publishing 'The Jewish State' in 1896","The First Zionist Congress was held in Basel, Switzerland, in 1897","The movement led to the establishment of the State of Israel on May 14, 1948"]},"slave revolt":{"desc":"Throughout history, enslaved people fought back against slavery in many dramatic revolts. These uprisings, from ancient Rome to the Americas, showed the courage of enslaved people who risked everything for their freedom.","facts":["The Haitian Revolution (1791-1804) was the most successful slave revolt, leading to Haiti becoming a free country","Nat Turner led a slave rebellion in Virginia in August 1831 that killed about 55 white people","Spartacus led a famous slave revolt against ancient Rome from 73 to 71 BC with an army of about 70,000"]},"1988 Winter Olympics":{"desc":"The 1988 Winter Olympics were held in Calgary, Alberta, Canada, from February 13 to 28, 1988. These games are remembered for several historic moments, including the debut of the Jamaican bobsled team.","facts":["The Soviet Union led the medal count with 29 total medals","Eddie 'The Eagle' Edwards from Great Britain became famous as a lovable underdog in ski jumping","Figure skater Katarina Witt of East Germany won her second consecutive Olympic gold medal"]},"Aboriginal peoples":{"desc":"Aboriginal peoples are the original inhabitants of Australia who have lived on the continent for tens of thousands of years. They have the oldest continuing culture in the world, with rich traditions of art, music, and storytelling called the Dreamtime.","facts":["Aboriginal Australians have lived in Australia for at least 65,000 years","There were around 250 distinct language groups before European arrival in 1788","The Dreamtime is the Aboriginal belief system explaining the creation of the world and all living things"]},"Abu Bakr":{"desc":"Abu Bakr was one of the closest friends and followers of the Prophet Muhammad and became the first Caliph, or leader, of the Muslim community after Muhammad died in 632 AD. He helped hold the young Muslim community together during a difficult time and began spreading Islam beyond the Arabian Peninsula.","facts":["He was the first adult male to convert to Islam and was Muhammad's father-in-law","He ruled as Caliph for only about two years, from 632 to 634 AD","He fought the Ridda Wars (Wars of Apostasy) against Arab tribes that tried to leave Islam after Muhammad's death"]},"Acropolis":{"desc":"The Acropolis is a flat-topped rocky hill in the center of Athens, Greece, that holds some of the most famous ancient buildings in the world, including the Parthenon. It has been used as a fortress, a religious center, and a symbol of ancient Greek civilization for thousands of years.","facts":["The word 'Acropolis' means 'high city' in Greek, and the hill rises about 490 feet (150 meters) above sea level","The most famous buildings on the Acropolis, including the Parthenon, were built during the Age of Pericles in the 5th century BC","In 1687, a Venetian cannonball hit the Parthenon, which the Ottomans were using to store gunpowder, causing a massive explosion that destroyed much of the building"]},"Adventures of Huckleberry Finn":{"desc":"Adventures of Huckleberry Finn is a novel by Mark Twain published in 1884 that tells the story of a boy named Huck who travels down the Mississippi River on a raft with an escaped slave named Jim. It is considered one of the greatest American novels ever written.","facts":["Mark Twain's real name was Samuel Clemens","The book is set in the pre-Civil War South along the Mississippi River","It was first published in the United Kingdom in December 1884 and in the United States in February 1885"]},"Aksum Kingdom":{"desc":"The Kingdom of Aksum was a powerful ancient civilization located in what is now Ethiopia and Eritrea, thriving from about 100 to 940 AD. It was one of the four great powers of the ancient world and was the first major African kingdom to adopt Christianity.","facts":["King Ezana converted the kingdom to Christianity around 330 AD, making Aksum one of the earliest Christian states","Aksum was a major trading empire with its own coins and a port city called Adulis on the Red Sea","The kingdom built giant stone obelisks called stelae, the tallest of which stood about 100 feet (33 meters) tall"]},"Anne Boleyn":{"desc":"Anne Boleyn was the second wife of King Henry VIII of England and the mother of Queen Elizabeth I. Henry VIII broke away from the Catholic Church partly so he could marry Anne, but she was later accused of treason and executed in 1536.","facts":["She was executed on May 19, 1536, at the Tower of London","Her daughter Elizabeth became Queen Elizabeth I, one of England's greatest monarchs","Henry VIII created the Church of England in part so he could annul his first marriage and marry Anne"]},"Anthony Albanese":{"desc":"Anthony Albanese is the 31st Prime Minister of Australia, taking office on May 23, 2022. He is the leader of the Australian Labor Party and grew up in public housing in Sydney.","facts":["He was born on March 2, 1963, in Sydney, Australia","He served as Deputy Prime Minister under Kevin Rudd from 2013 to 2013","He became Leader of the Australian Labor Party in 2019 after the party's election loss"]},"Apollo program":{"desc":"The Apollo program was NASA's space program that successfully landed humans on the Moon. It ran from 1961 to 1972 and is one of the greatest achievements in human history.","facts":["Apollo 11 made the first Moon landing on July 20, 1969, with astronauts Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin","There were six successful Moon landings in total, with 12 astronauts walking on the Moon","The Apollo 13 mission in 1970 had an explosion in space but the crew safely returned to Earth"]},"Appomattox Court House":{"desc":"Appomattox Court House is a small village in Virginia where Confederate General Robert E. Lee surrendered to Union General Ulysses S. Grant on April 9, 1865, effectively ending the Civil War. The surrender took place in the parlor of Wilmer McLean's house.","facts":["Lee surrendered approximately 28,000 Confederate soldiers","Grant allowed Confederate soldiers to keep their horses and go home peacefully","The surrender came just six days after the fall of the Confederate capital of Richmond, Virginia"]},"Argentina":{"desc":"Argentina is a large country in the southern part of South America. It declared independence from Spain on July 9, 1816, and has grown into one of the biggest and most important countries in Latin America.","facts":["Argentina declared independence from Spain on July 9, 1816","Buenos Aires is the capital and largest city","Argentina is the second-largest country in South America after Brazil"]},"Assyrian Empire":{"desc":"The Assyrian Empire was one of the most powerful and feared empires of the ancient world, ruling a huge area of the Middle East from about 2500 BC to 609 BC. The Assyrians were known for their mighty army, advanced siege weapons, and their sometimes cruel treatment of conquered peoples.","facts":["At its peak around 670 BC, the Neo-Assyrian Empire stretched from Egypt to western Iran","The capital city of Nineveh had massive walls 7.5 miles long and a great library built by King Ashurbanipal containing over 30,000 clay tablets","The empire fell in 612 BC when a coalition of Babylonians and Medes conquered and destroyed Nineveh"]},"Augusto Pinochet":{"desc":"Augusto Pinochet was a military dictator who ruled Chile from 1973 to 1990. He took power by overthrowing the elected president Salvador Allende in a violent military coup and ruled the country harshly for 17 years.","facts":["Pinochet seized power in a coup on September 11, 1973","He ruled Chile as a military dictator until 1990","Thousands of people were killed or disappeared under his rule"]},"Aung San Suu Kyi":{"desc":"Aung San Suu Kyi is a political leader from Myanmar (also called Burma) who spent many years fighting for democracy against a military government. She won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1991 while under house arrest, but her reputation was later damaged when she did not speak out against the treatment of the Rohingya people.","facts":["She spent about 15 of the 21 years between 1989 and 2010 under house arrest by Myanmar's military rulers","Her political party, the National League for Democracy, won a landslide election victory in 2015","She was arrested again in a military coup on February 1, 2021, and sentenced to prison"]},"Barbara Walters":{"desc":"Barbara Walters was a pioneering American journalist who broke barriers for women in television news. She was the first woman to co-anchor a network evening news program and became famous for her interviews with world leaders and celebrities.","facts":["She co-created and co-hosted the talk show The View, which premiered in 1997","She became the first female co-anchor of a network evening news show on ABC in 1976","She was born on September 25, 1929, and passed away on December 30, 2022"]},"Battle of Manila Bay":{"desc":"The Battle of Manila Bay was a naval battle during the Spanish-American War fought on May 1, 1898, in the Philippines. The American fleet, led by Commodore George Dewey, destroyed the entire Spanish fleet in just a few hours without losing a single American sailor.","facts":["Commodore George Dewey commanded the U.S. Asiatic Squadron in the battle","The battle took place on May 1, 1898, and lasted about seven hours","The Spanish lost all seven of their warships while the Americans suffered no ship losses and zero deaths in combat"]},"Battle of the Milvian Bridge":{"desc":"The Battle of the Milvian Bridge was fought in 312 AD near Rome between the Roman emperors Constantine and Maxentius. Before the battle, Constantine reportedly saw a vision of a Christian cross in the sky, and after his victory he became the first Roman emperor to support Christianity.","facts":["The battle took place on October 28, 312 AD, at the Milvian Bridge over the Tiber River","Constantine's opponent Maxentius drowned in the Tiber River during the battle","After his victory, Constantine issued the Edict of Milan in 313 AD, allowing Christians to worship freely"]},"Bear Flag Republic":{"desc":"The Bear Flag Republic was a short-lived attempt by American settlers in California to create their own country in 1846. A group of settlers captured the town of Sonoma and raised a flag with a grizzly bear on it, which later inspired the California state flag.","facts":["The Bear Flag Revolt began on June 14, 1846, in Sonoma, California","The republic lasted only about 25 days before being absorbed into the United States","The bear flag design became the basis for California's official state flag"]},"Bhutan":{"desc":"Bhutan is a small Buddhist kingdom located in the Himalaya Mountains between China and India. It is famous for measuring its success not just by money but by something called 'Gross National Happiness,' which looks at how content and well its people are.","facts":["Bhutan did not have television or internet until 1999, making it one of the last countries to introduce TV","The country measures Gross National Happiness instead of just Gross Domestic Product","Bhutan is the world's only carbon-negative country, meaning its forests absorb more carbon dioxide than the country produces"]},"Black Plague":{"desc":"The Black Plague, also called the Black Death, was a terrible disease that swept through Europe in the 1340s and killed millions of people. It was one of the deadliest pandemics in human history, wiping out roughly one-third of Europe's population in just a few years.","facts":["The Black Death peaked in Europe between 1347 and 1353","It killed an estimated 25 to 50 million people in Europe","The disease was caused by the bacterium Yersinia pestis and was spread by fleas on rats"]},"Boer Wars":{"desc":"The Boer Wars were two wars fought between the British Empire and the Boers (Dutch-speaking settlers) in southern Africa. The Second Boer War (1899-1902) was especially important because the British used controversial concentration camps and it eventually led to the creation of the Union of South Africa.","facts":["The First Boer War (1880-1881) was a short conflict that the Boers won, keeping their independence","During the Second Boer War (1899-1902), the British placed Boer women and children in concentration camps where about 26,000 died from disease","The war ended with the Treaty of Vereeniging in 1902, and in 1910 the British and Boer territories merged into the Union of South Africa"]},"Bohemia":{"desc":"Bohemia is a historical region in central Europe that is now the western part of the Czech Republic. For centuries it was an important kingdom with its capital in Prague, and it played a key role in European events like the start of the Thirty Years' War.","facts":["Prague, the capital of Bohemia, has been a major European city since the Middle Ages","The Defenestration of Prague in 1618, when Protestant nobles threw Catholic officials out of a window, helped start the Thirty Years' War","Bohemia was part of the Habsburg Empire from 1526 until 1918"]},"Bongbong Marcos":{"desc":"Bongbong Marcos, whose full name is Ferdinand Marcos Jr., is the current President of the Philippines and the son of former dictator Ferdinand Marcos Sr. His father ruled the Philippines for 20 years and was overthrown in the 1986 People Power Revolution, but the family returned to politics decades later.","facts":["He won the Philippine presidential election in May 2022 with over 31 million votes","His father, Ferdinand Marcos Sr., declared martial law in 1972 and ruled as a dictator until being overthrown in 1986","The Marcos family was accused of stealing billions of dollars from the Philippines during their time in power"]},"Book of Kells":{"desc":"The Book of Kells is a beautifully decorated manuscript of the four Gospels of the Bible, created by Celtic monks around the year 800 AD. It is considered one of the greatest masterpieces of medieval art, with incredibly detailed illustrations, colorful designs, and intricate letter decorations on nearly every page.","facts":["It was likely created around 800 AD by monks at the monastery of Iona, off the coast of Scotland, and later moved to Kells, Ireland","The book contains 680 pages of elaborate illustrations using pigments from as far away as Afghanistan","It has been kept at Trinity College Dublin since 1661 and is Ireland's most famous national treasure"]},"Booker T. Washington":{"desc":"Booker T. Washington was an African American educator and leader who founded the Tuskegee Institute in Alabama in 1881. He believed that education and economic self-improvement were the best paths for Black Americans to gain equality after slavery.","facts":["He was born into slavery in 1856 in Virginia and was freed after the Civil War","His autobiography, Up From Slavery, published in 1901, became a bestseller","He was the first African American invited to dine at the White House, by President Theodore Roosevelt in 1901"]},"Brexit":{"desc":"Brexit is the name for the United Kingdom's decision to leave the European Union. In a public vote called a referendum held on June 23, 2016, about 52% of British voters chose to leave the EU, and the UK officially left on January 31, 2020.","facts":["The referendum was held on June 23, 2016, and 51.9% voted to leave","The UK officially left the European Union on January 31, 2020","The word Brexit is a combination of 'Britain' and 'exit'"]},"Brigham Young":{"desc":"Brigham Young was the second president of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (the Mormon Church) and led thousands of Mormon settlers to the Salt Lake Valley in Utah in 1847. He served as the first governor of the Utah Territory.","facts":["He led approximately 70,000 Mormon pioneers westward to Utah","He founded Brigham Young University in Provo, Utah, in 1875","He was governor of the Utah Territory from 1850 to 1858"]},"Buddhist statues":{"desc":"Throughout history, people have built giant statues of the Buddha to show their devotion and faith. Some of the most famous Buddhist statues are hundreds of feet tall and took many years to carve or build, but sadly some have been destroyed by war and conflict.","facts":["The Bamiyan Buddhas in Afghanistan, carved in the 6th century and standing 180 and 121 feet tall, were destroyed by the Taliban in March 2001","The Great Buddha at Leshan in China, carved between 713 and 803 AD, stands 233 feet tall and is the largest stone Buddha in the world","The Great Buddha at Kamakura in Japan was built in 1252 and originally sat inside a wooden temple that was washed away by a tsunami in 1498"]},"Byzantine Empire":{"desc":"The Byzantine Empire was the eastern continuation of the Roman Empire, lasting from 330 CE when Constantine moved the capital to Constantinople until its fall to the Ottoman Turks in 1453. It preserved Greek and Roman knowledge through the Middle Ages and was known for its art, architecture, and the Justinian Code of laws.","facts":["Eastern continuation of the Roman Empire (330-1453 CE)","Capital was Constantinople (modern Istanbul)","Emperor Justinian created a famous code of laws","Built the magnificent Hagia Sophia cathedral","Preserved Greek and Roman learning during the Dark Ages"]},"Canadian Confederation":{"desc":"Canadian Confederation was the process by which three British colonies joined together on July 1, 1867, to form the Dominion of Canada. This date is now celebrated as Canada Day, the country's national holiday.","facts":["The original four provinces were Ontario, Quebec, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick","The British North America Act of 1867 served as Canada's constitution for over a century","Sir John A. Macdonald became Canada's first Prime Minister"]},"Cecil Rhodes":{"desc":"Cecil Rhodes was a British businessman and politician who became extremely wealthy from diamond mining in southern Africa in the late 1800s. He founded the De Beers diamond company, became Prime Minister of the Cape Colony, and his actions helped Britain colonize large parts of Africa.","facts":["He founded the De Beers diamond company, which at one point controlled about 90% of the world's diamond production","He served as Prime Minister of the Cape Colony (now part of South Africa) from 1890 to 1896","The countries of Northern Rhodesia (now Zambia) and Southern Rhodesia (now Zimbabwe) were named after him"]},"Cherokee Nation":{"desc":"The Cherokee Nation is one of the largest Native American tribes in the United States, originally from the southeastern United States. They were one of the 'Five Civilized Tribes' and were forced to walk the Trail of Tears to Oklahoma in the 1830s.","facts":["The Trail of Tears in 1838-1839 forced about 16,000 Cherokee to relocate, and roughly 4,000 died on the journey","The Cherokee developed their own written language using a syllabary created by Sequoyah","Today the Cherokee Nation is headquartered in Tahlequah, Oklahoma, and has over 400,000 enrolled citizens"]},"Colombia":{"desc":"Colombia is a country in the northwestern part of South America, named after the explorer Christopher Columbus. It gained independence from Spain in 1819 after a war led by the famous general Simón Bolívar.","facts":["Colombia gained independence from Spain on August 7, 1819","The country is named after Christopher Columbus","Bogotá is the capital and largest city of Colombia"]},"Comoros":{"desc":"Comoros is a small island nation located in the Indian Ocean between Madagascar and the coast of East Africa. It has a long history of Arab, African, and French influence and is one of the smallest and poorest countries in Africa, but it has a rich cultural heritage.","facts":["The country is made up of three main islands: Grande Comore, Moheli, and Anjouan, while a fourth island, Mayotte, voted to remain part of France","Comoros gained independence from France on July 6, 1975, and has experienced more than 20 coups or attempted coups since then","Arab traders and settlers arrived as early as the 6th century, bringing Islam, which is now the dominant religion"]},"Crazy Horse":{"desc":"Crazy Horse was an Oglala Lakota war leader who fought to preserve the traditions and land of his people against the U.S. government. He is best known for his role in defeating General Custer at the Battle of the Little Bighorn in 1876.","facts":["He was born around 1840 in present-day South Dakota","He surrendered to U.S. troops in May 1877 and was killed at Fort Robinson, Nebraska, on September 5, 1877","The Crazy Horse Memorial, a massive mountain carving in the Black Hills of South Dakota, has been under construction since 1948"]},"Declaration of Independence":{"desc":"On July 4, 1776, the Continental Congress adopted the Declaration of Independence, written mainly by Thomas Jefferson. It declared the 13 American colonies free from British rule. In 2026, America celebrates its 250th birthday, called the 'semiquincentennial.' The Declaration stated that 'all men are created equal' and listed grievances against King George III. The original document is kept at the National Archives in Washington, D.C.","facts":["Only 2 of the 56 signers later became president: John Adams and Thomas Jefferson","Both Adams and Jefferson died on the same day: July 4, 1826 — the 50th anniversary","Benjamin Franklin, at 70, was the oldest signer","The Declaration was approved on July 2 but not signed until August 2","The 250th celebration in 2026 includes Freedom Trucks visiting all 48 contiguous states"]},"Diego Rivera":{"desc":"Diego Rivera was a famous Mexican artist known for painting enormous, colorful murals on the walls of public buildings. His murals often showed scenes of Mexican history, workers, and everyday life, and he is considered one of the greatest muralists of the 20th century.","facts":["He was born on December 8, 1886, in Guanajuato, Mexico","He painted a famous mural at the Detroit Institute of Arts called Detroit Industry in 1932–1933","He was married to fellow artist Frida Kahlo, and they had a famously stormy relationship"]},"Doctors' Plot":{"desc":"The Doctors' Plot was a made-up conspiracy in the Soviet Union in 1953 where Soviet leader Joseph Stalin accused a group of mostly Jewish doctors of plotting to poison top Soviet leaders. The accusations were false and were part of Stalin's paranoia, but the crisis ended when Stalin died in March 1953.","facts":["The plot was announced by the Soviet government on January 13, 1953","Nine doctors were arrested, six of whom were Jewish, fueling antisemitic persecution","The charges were dropped shortly after Stalin's death on March 5, 1953"]},"Doolittle Raid":{"desc":"The Doolittle Raid was a daring American bombing attack on Tokyo, Japan, on April 18, 1942, during World War II. It was the first time the United States bombed the Japanese homeland, and while it did not cause huge damage, it gave Americans hope and showed Japan that it could be attacked.","facts":["Lieutenant Colonel James Doolittle led 16 B-25 bombers that launched from the aircraft carrier USS Hornet","The planes could not land back on the carrier, so most crews crash-landed in China or bailed out by parachute","Three airmen were executed by the Japanese after being captured, and the raid pushed Japan to attack Midway, leading to a major American victory"]},"Eli Whitney":{"desc":"Eli Whitney was an American inventor best known for inventing the cotton gin in 1793, which made it much faster to separate cotton fibers from seeds. He also pioneered the idea of interchangeable parts in manufacturing, which changed how things were built in factories.","facts":["The cotton gin could clean 50 pounds of cotton per day compared to 1 pound by hand","He was born on December 8, 1765, in Westborough, Massachusetts","His concept of interchangeable parts, used in making muskets for the U.S. government, helped lead to the American Industrial Revolution"]},"Estado Novo":{"desc":"Estado Novo, meaning 'New State' in Portuguese, was the authoritarian government that ruled Portugal from 1933 to 1974 under dictators António de Oliveira Salazar and later Marcelo Caetano. It was one of the longest-lasting dictatorships in Western Europe and was finally overthrown by a peaceful military revolution.","facts":["António de Oliveira Salazar led Portugal from 1932 until a stroke forced him out in 1968","The regime was overthrown on April 25, 1974, in the Carnation Revolution, named because soldiers put carnations in their gun barrels","Portugal held onto African colonies like Angola and Mozambique longer than most European countries, partly due to the Estado Novo's policies"]},"Ethiopian Empire":{"desc":"The Ethiopian Empire, also known as Abyssinia, was one of the longest-lasting empires in African history, existing in various forms for nearly 700 years until 1974. Ethiopia is unique in Africa because it was never colonized by a European power, successfully defeating an Italian invasion in 1896.","facts":["Ethiopia defeated Italy at the Battle of Adwa on March 1, 1896, preserving its independence during the Scramble for Africa","The Solomonic Dynasty, which ruled Ethiopia for centuries, claimed descent from King Solomon and the Queen of Sheba","Emperor Haile Selassie, the last emperor, ruled from 1930 until he was overthrown by a communist military group in 1974"]},"European Space Agency":{"desc":"The European Space Agency (ESA) is a space exploration organization made up of many European countries working together. Founded in 1975, it launches rockets, sends probes to other planets, and helps build the International Space Station.","facts":["ESA was founded on May 30, 1975, and has 22 member states","Its main spaceport is located in Kourou, French Guiana","ESA's Rosetta mission successfully landed a probe on a comet for the first time in November 2014"]},"European Union":{"desc":"The European Union is a group of European countries that work together on things like trade, travel, and laws. It started as a small group of six countries after World War II to promote peace and has grown to include 27 member nations today.","facts":["It began in 1957 when six countries signed the Treaty of Rome","The euro currency was introduced on January 1, 1999, and is now used by 20 EU member countries","The EU headquarters are located in Brussels, Belgium"]},"F. Scott Fitzgerald":{"desc":"F. Scott Fitzgerald was an American author who is best known for his novel The Great Gatsby, published in 1925. He is considered one of the greatest writers of the 20th century and his work captured the spirit of the 1920s, which he called the 'Jazz Age.'","facts":["He was born on September 24, 1896, in St. Paul, Minnesota","The Great Gatsby was not very popular during his lifetime but is now considered a classic of American literature","He died on December 21, 1940, at age 44 in Hollywood, California"]},"FARC":{"desc":"FARC stands for the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, a rebel guerrilla group that fought the Colombian government for over 50 years. They wanted to change Colombia's government and help poor farmers, but they also used violence and were involved in illegal activities.","facts":["FARC was founded in 1964 as a Marxist guerrilla group","A peace deal was signed between FARC and the Colombian government in 2016","At its peak, FARC had around 20,000 fighters"]},"Falklands War":{"desc":"The Falklands War was a short but intense conflict in 1982 between the United Kingdom and Argentina over control of the Falkland Islands, a small group of islands in the South Atlantic Ocean. Argentina invaded the islands in April, but British forces fought back and won the war in just 74 days.","facts":["The war lasted from April 2 to June 14, 1982","About 649 Argentine and 255 British soldiers were killed during the conflict","British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's popularity surged after the British victory"]},"Ferdinand and Isabella":{"desc":"Ferdinand and Isabella were the king and queen of Spain who united the country and funded Christopher Columbus's famous voyage in 1492. Their marriage in 1469 joined the kingdoms of Aragon and Castile, creating the powerful nation of Spain.","facts":["Ferdinand of Aragon and Isabella of Castile married on October 19, 1469","They sponsored Christopher Columbus's first voyage to the Americas in 1492","They completed the Reconquista by conquering Granada, the last Muslim territory in Spain, in January 1492"]},"Filibuster":{"desc":"A filibuster is a tactic used in the United States Senate where a senator gives a very long speech or uses other delaying methods to block or delay a vote on a bill. It takes 60 out of 100 senators to vote to end a filibuster, which is called 'cloture.'","facts":["The longest filibuster in U.S. history was by Senator Strom Thurmond, who spoke for 24 hours and 18 minutes in 1957 to block a civil rights bill","The word 'filibuster' comes from a Spanish word meaning 'pirate'","The cloture rule requiring 60 votes to end a filibuster was established in 1917"]},"Five Civilized Tribes":{"desc":"The Five Civilized Tribes is a term used for five Native American nations — the Cherokee, Chickasaw, Choctaw, Creek (Muscogee), and Seminole — who adopted many European-American customs. They were forcibly relocated from the southeastern United States to Indian Territory (now Oklahoma) during the 1830s.","facts":["The forced removal is known as the Trail of Tears and was carried out under President Andrew Jackson's Indian Removal Act of 1830","The tribes were called 'civilized' because they had adopted practices like written constitutions, farming, and formal education","Each tribe established its own government and capital in Indian Territory (present-day Oklahoma)"]},"Flight of the Bumblebees":{"desc":"Flight of the Bumblebee is a famous orchestral piece written by Russian composer Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov in 1900. The music is extremely fast and is meant to sound like a buzzing bumblebee flying around, making it one of the most recognizable pieces of classical music.","facts":["It was composed by Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov around 1899-1900","The piece comes from his opera 'The Tale of Tsar Saltan'","It is often used as a showcase piece for musicians because it requires playing very fast notes"]},"Frank Sinatra":{"desc":"Frank Sinatra was one of the most famous American singers and actors of the 20th century, known for his smooth voice and songs like 'My Way' and 'Fly Me to the Moon.' He was a major cultural figure from the 1940s through the 1990s and won an Academy Award for acting.","facts":["He was born on December 12, 1915, in Hoboken, New Jersey","He won the Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor for the 1953 film From Here to Eternity","He was a member of the Rat Pack, a famous group of entertainers that included Dean Martin and Sammy Davis Jr."]},"French Guiana":{"desc":"French Guiana is a territory on the northeastern coast of South America that belongs to France. It is the only part of mainland South America that is still governed by a European country, and today it is famous for its space launch center.","facts":["French Guiana is an overseas department of France, not an independent country","The Guiana Space Centre in Kourou is used by the European Space Agency to launch rockets","Devil's Island, a famous prison, was located off its coast and operated from 1852 to 1953"]},"Frida Kahlo":{"desc":"Frida Kahlo was a Mexican artist famous for her vivid, emotional self-portraits that often depicted her physical pain and Mexican culture. She overcame a terrible bus accident at age 18 that left her with lifelong injuries, and she turned her suffering into powerful art.","facts":["She was born on July 6, 1907, in Coyoacán, Mexico City","About 55 of her 143 paintings are self-portraits","She was married to muralist Diego Rivera and their house in Mexico City, called the Blue House, is now a museum"]},"Gandhi and Nehru":{"desc":"Mahatma Gandhi and Jawaharlal Nehru were two of the most important leaders in India's fight for independence from British rule. Gandhi was known for his nonviolent protests, while Nehru became India's first Prime Minister after independence in 1947 and helped build the new nation.","facts":["Gandhi was assassinated on January 30, 1948, by Nathuram Godse, a Hindu nationalist","Nehru served as India's first Prime Minister from 1947 until his death in 1964","Gandhi called Nehru his political heir, and together they led the Indian National Congress party during the independence movement"]},"George McClellan":{"desc":"George B. McClellan was a Union general during the Civil War who commanded the Army of the Potomac and briefly served as General-in-Chief of all Union armies. He was known for training and organizing the army well but was criticized for being too cautious in battle.","facts":["President Lincoln removed him from command twice because of his reluctance to aggressively pursue the Confederate army","He ran against Abraham Lincoln as the Democratic candidate in the 1864 presidential election and lost","He won the Battle of Antietam on September 17, 1862, which was the single bloodiest day in American history"]},"George W. Bush":{"desc":"George W. Bush was the 43rd President of the United States, serving from 2001 to 2009. He led the country's response after the September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks, including launching wars in Afghanistan and Iraq.","facts":["He is the son of George H.W. Bush, the 41st president, making them the second father-son pair to both serve as president","He won the 2000 election against Al Gore in one of the closest elections ever, decided by the Supreme Court in Bush v. Gore","He signed the No Child Left Behind Act in 2002, a major education reform law"]},"Glasnost":{"desc":"Glasnost is a Russian word meaning 'openness,' and it was a policy introduced by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev in the 1980s. It allowed Soviet citizens more freedom to speak openly, read uncensored news, and criticize the government, which helped lead to the end of the Soviet Union.","facts":["Glasnost was introduced by Mikhail Gorbachev starting in 1986","It was paired with another reform called perestroika, meaning 'restructuring' of the economy","These reforms contributed to the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989 and the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991"]},"Grameen Bank":{"desc":"The Grameen Bank is a special bank in Bangladesh that gives tiny loans to very poor people, especially women, who cannot borrow from regular banks. It was founded by Muhammad Yunus to help poor people start small businesses and lift themselves out of poverty.","facts":["Founded by Muhammad Yunus in 1983, the bank has loaned over $30 billion to nearly 10 million borrowers","About 97% of Grameen Bank's borrowers are women","Muhammad Yunus and the Grameen Bank together won the Nobel Peace Prize in 2006 for their work fighting poverty"]},"Green Eggs and Ham":{"desc":"Green Eggs and Ham is one of the most famous children's books ever written, created by Dr. Seuss (Theodor Geisel) in 1960. The entire book uses only 50 different words because Dr. Seuss wrote it on a bet that he couldn't write a book with so few words.","facts":["The book was published in 1960 and written by Dr. Seuss (Theodor Seuss Geisel)","It uses only 50 unique words throughout the entire story","Dr. Seuss wrote it after his editor Bennett Cerf bet him he couldn't write a book using 50 words or fewer"]},"Guru Nanak":{"desc":"Guru Nanak was the founder of Sikhism, one of the world's major religions, born in 1469 in what is now Pakistan. He taught that there is one God, that all people are equal regardless of their religion or social class, and that people should live honestly and share with others.","facts":["He was born in 1469 in Talwandi (now called Nankana Sahib) in present-day Pakistan","He traveled widely for about 28 years on journeys called Udasis, visiting places across South Asia and possibly the Middle East","He was the first of ten Sikh Gurus, and his teachings are recorded in the Guru Granth Sahib, the Sikh holy scripture"]},"Hamilton musical":{"desc":"Hamilton is a hit Broadway musical created by Lin-Manuel Miranda that tells the story of Founding Father Alexander Hamilton using hip-hop and R&B music. It opened on Broadway in August 2015 and became one of the most popular musicals in history.","facts":["It won 11 Tony Awards in 2016, including Best Musical","Lin-Manuel Miranda was inspired to write it after reading Ron Chernow's biography of Alexander Hamilton","The show features a diverse cast portraying the Founding Fathers, which was a groundbreaking creative choice"]},"Hammurabi":{"desc":"Hammurabi was a king of Babylon who ruled from about 1792 to 1750 BCE. He is best known for the Code of Hammurabi, one of the oldest written sets of laws ever discovered. The code was carved into a stone pillar and included the famous principle of 'an eye for an eye.'","facts":["King of Babylon (c. 1792-1750 BCE)","Created the Code of Hammurabi, one of the oldest written law codes","The code contained 282 laws carved on a stone pillar","Famous for the principle 'an eye for an eye'","The code covered trade, property, family, and criminal law"]},"Han Dynasty":{"desc":"The Han Dynasty ruled China from 206 BC to 220 AD and is considered one of the greatest periods in Chinese history. It was so important that the majority ethnic group in China today still calls itself 'Han Chinese,' and the dynasty established the Silk Road trade route connecting China to the Roman Empire.","facts":["The Silk Road trade routes were formally established during Emperor Wu's reign around 130 BC","Paper was invented during the Han Dynasty, traditionally credited to Cai Lun around 105 AD","The Han Dynasty lasted over 400 years and is divided into Western Han (206 BC-9 AD) and Eastern Han (25-220 AD)"]},"Harpers Ferry":{"desc":"Harpers Ferry is a small town in present-day West Virginia where John Brown led a famous raid on the federal armory on October 16, 1859, in an attempt to start a slave rebellion. The town also played an important role during the Civil War because of its strategic location where two rivers meet.","facts":["John Brown and 21 followers seized the armory but were captured by U.S. Marines led by Colonel Robert E. Lee","The town changed hands between Union and Confederate forces eight times during the Civil War","In September 1862, Confederate General Stonewall Jackson captured Harpers Ferry along with about 12,500 Union soldiers, the largest Union surrender during the war"]},"Herod the Great":{"desc":"Herod the Great was the king of Judea from 37 to 4 BC, ruling under the authority of the Roman Empire. He is famous for his massive building projects, including expanding the Second Temple in Jerusalem, but he is also remembered for his cruelty and paranoia about losing his throne.","facts":["He rebuilt and expanded the Second Temple in Jerusalem, making it one of the most magnificent buildings in the ancient world","According to the Gospel of Matthew, he ordered the Massacre of the Innocents, killing young boys in Bethlehem","He built the fortress of Masada and the port city of Caesarea, both engineering marvels of the ancient world"]},"Ho Chi Minh":{"desc":"Ho Chi Minh was the leader of Vietnam's independence movement and became the first president of North Vietnam. He fought against French colonial rule and later against the United States during the Vietnam War, and today Vietnam's largest city is named Ho Chi Minh City in his honor.","facts":["He declared Vietnam's independence from France on September 2, 1945, quoting the American Declaration of Independence","He lived abroad for about 30 years, traveling to France, the Soviet Union, and China before returning to lead Vietnam","He died on September 2, 1969, six years before the end of the Vietnam War and the reunification of Vietnam"]},"Hollywood sign":{"desc":"The Hollywood sign is a famous landmark in the Hollywood Hills of Los Angeles, California, with giant white letters spelling out 'HOLLYWOOD.' It was originally built in 1923 as an advertisement for a real estate development and originally read 'HOLLYWOODLAND.'","facts":["Each letter is about 45 feet tall","The 'LAND' part was removed in 1949 when the Hollywood Chamber of Commerce took over the sign","The sign was rebuilt in 1978 with steel letters after the original wooden ones had deteriorated"]},"Holodomor":{"desc":"The Holodomor was a devastating man-made famine in Soviet Ukraine in 1932–1933 caused by the policies of Soviet leader Joseph Stalin. Millions of Ukrainians starved to death when the Soviet government seized their grain and food, and many countries today recognize it as a genocide.","facts":["An estimated 3.5 to 7 million Ukrainians died during the famine of 1932–1933","The word Holodomor comes from Ukrainian words meaning 'death by starvation'","The Soviet government denied the famine was happening and blocked outside aid from reaching Ukraine"]},"Honduras":{"desc":"Honduras is a country in Central America that was once part of the ancient Maya civilization. It became independent from Spain in 1821 and has a history shaped by agriculture, especially banana farming.","facts":["Honduras gained independence from Spain on September 15, 1821","The ancient Maya city of Copán is located in western Honduras","Honduras was one of the original 'banana republics' where American fruit companies had enormous influence"]},"House of Tudor":{"desc":"The House of Tudor was a royal family that ruled England from 1485 to 1603, and it included some of the most famous kings and queens in English history. The Tudor period saw huge changes including the break from the Catholic Church and the beginning of England's rise as a world power.","facts":["The Tudor dynasty began when Henry VII won the Battle of Bosworth Field in 1485","Henry VIII, the second Tudor king, had six wives and created the Church of England","The last Tudor monarch was Queen Elizabeth I, who ruled from 1558 to 1603"]},"Howard Carter":{"desc":"Howard Carter was a British archaeologist who discovered the tomb of the pharaoh Tutankhamun in Egypt's Valley of the Kings in 1922. It was one of the greatest archaeological discoveries ever made because the tomb was nearly intact and filled with thousands of treasures, including the famous golden death mask.","facts":["He discovered Tutankhamun's tomb on November 4, 1922, after searching for it for five years, funded by Lord Carnarvon","The tomb contained over 5,000 artifacts, including the iconic solid gold death mask weighing about 24 pounds","Lord Carnarvon died shortly after the tomb was opened, leading newspapers to write about a supposed 'Curse of the Pharaohs'"]},"Hugh Capet":{"desc":"Hugh Capet was the first king of the Capetian dynasty, which ruled France starting in 987 AD. He may not be very well known, but his family became one of the most successful royal dynasties in European history, with his descendants ruling France for over 800 years.","facts":["He was elected King of France in 987 AD after the death of the last Carolingian king, Louis V","The Capetian dynasty he founded ruled France directly until 1328, and its branches (Valois and Bourbon) continued until 1848","He was the Duke of Francia and Count of Paris before becoming king, and he cleverly had his son crowned during his own lifetime to secure the succession"]},"Hugo Chavez":{"desc":"Hugo Chávez was the president of Venezuela from 1999 until his death in 2013. He used Venezuela's oil wealth to fund social programs for the poor, but he was also criticized for limiting freedoms and concentrating too much power in his own hands.","facts":["Chávez first tried to take power in a failed military coup in 1992","He was elected president of Venezuela in 1998","He died of cancer on March 5, 2013"]},"Ivan the Terrible":{"desc":"Ivan the Terrible was the first ruler of Russia to take the title of Tsar, and he ruled from 1547 to 1584. He earned his fearsome nickname because of his violent temper and cruel punishments, but he also expanded Russia's territory and strengthened its government.","facts":["He became the first Tsar of Russia in 1547 at the age of 16","He ordered the construction of St. Basil's Cathedral in Moscow, which was completed in 1561","In a fit of rage in 1581, he struck and killed his own son, Ivan"]},"Ivory Coast":{"desc":"Ivory Coast, officially called Cote d'Ivoire, is a country in West Africa that was a French colony until it gained independence in 1960. It became one of the most prosperous countries in West Africa thanks to its cocoa farming, producing more cocoa beans than any other country in the world.","facts":["Ivory Coast produces about 40% of the world's cocoa, making it the largest cocoa producer on Earth","Felix Houphouet-Boigny was the country's first president, ruling from independence in 1960 until his death in 1993","The Basilica of Our Lady of Peace in Yamoussoukro, completed in 1989, is the largest church in the world by area"]},"James I of England":{"desc":"James I became King of England in 1603 after Queen Elizabeth I died, and he was already King James VI of Scotland, so he united the two crowns. He is well known for authorizing a new English translation of the Bible, called the King James Bible, which is still widely used today.","facts":["He became King James VI of Scotland in 1567 when he was just one year old","He survived the Gunpowder Plot of 1605, when Guy Fawkes and others tried to blow up Parliament","He commissioned the King James Version of the Bible, published in 1611"]},"James K. Polk":{"desc":"James K. Polk was the 11th President of the United States, serving from 1845 to 1849. He is known for greatly expanding the nation's territory, including acquiring California and much of the Southwest through the Mexican-American War.","facts":["He oversaw the addition of more territory to the U.S. than any president since Thomas Jefferson","He is often called the first 'dark horse' presidential candidate because he was not expected to win the 1844 election","He kept his promise to serve only one term and died just three months after leaving office, on June 15, 1849"]},"Jan III Sobieski":{"desc":"Jan III Sobieski was the King of Poland from 1674 to 1696 and is remembered as one of Poland's greatest heroes. He is most famous for leading a massive cavalry charge that helped defeat the Ottoman Turkish army at the Battle of Vienna in 1683, saving the city from conquest.","facts":["He led the largest cavalry charge in history at the Battle of Vienna on September 12, 1683","His winged hussar cavalry helped break the Ottoman siege of Vienna","He ruled as King of Poland and Grand Duke of Lithuania from 1674 to 1696"]},"Johannesburg":{"desc":"Johannesburg is the largest city in South Africa and was founded in 1886 after gold was discovered in the area. The city grew incredibly fast because of the gold rush and became the economic center of South Africa, but it also became a symbol of the injustice of apartheid.","facts":["The city was founded in 1886 following the discovery of gold on the Witwatersrand ridge, sparking the largest gold rush in history","The Witwatersrand gold fields have produced about 40% of all the gold ever mined in the world","Nelson Mandela and other anti-apartheid leaders were tried in Johannesburg's Palace of Justice during the Rivonia Trial in 1963-1964"]},"John III Sobieski":{"desc":"John III Sobieski was the King of Poland from 1674 to 1696, and he is most famous for leading the charge that saved Vienna from a massive Ottoman Turkish siege in 1683. His victory at the Battle of Vienna is considered one of the most important battles in European history.","facts":["He became King of Poland in 1674 after winning fame as a military commander","He led the largest cavalry charge in history at the Battle of Vienna on September 12, 1683","His victory at Vienna stopped the Ottoman Empire from advancing further into Europe"]},"John Macdonald":{"desc":"Sir John A. Macdonald was the first Prime Minister of Canada, serving from 1867 to 1873 and again from 1878 to 1891. He played the biggest role in creating Canada as a united country through Confederation in 1867.","facts":["He became Canada's first Prime Minister on July 1, 1867, the day of Confederation","He served as Prime Minister for a total of about 19 years across two terms","He pushed for the building of the Canadian Pacific Railway to connect Canada from coast to coast"]},"Josip Broz Tito":{"desc":"Josip Broz Tito was the leader of Yugoslavia from 1945 until his death in 1980, and he was famous for keeping the country's many ethnic groups together. He was unusual among communist leaders because he stood up to Soviet leader Joseph Stalin and kept Yugoslavia independent from Soviet control.","facts":["He led the Yugoslav Partisans, one of the most effective resistance movements against the Nazis in World War II","He broke with Stalin and the Soviet Union in 1948, charting an independent path for Yugoslavia","After his death on May 4, 1980, Yugoslavia gradually fell apart and broke into several countries in the 1990s"]},"Juan Peron":{"desc":"Juan Perón was a powerful president of Argentina who served three terms. He and his famous wife Eva (Evita) Perón were beloved by many working-class Argentines because of their social programs, but he also ruled in an authoritarian way.","facts":["Perón served as president of Argentina from 1946 to 1955 and again briefly in 1973-1974","His second wife, Eva Perón (Evita), became a beloved national figure before her death in 1952","He was overthrown by a military coup in 1955 and lived in exile for 18 years"]},"Juan Ponce de León":{"desc":"Juan Ponce de León was a Spanish explorer who became the first European to reach Florida in 1513. He is famous in legends for searching for the Fountain of Youth, a magical spring that was said to make people young again.","facts":["He arrived in Florida in April 1513 and named it 'La Florida' meaning 'Land of Flowers'","He served as the first governor of Puerto Rico starting in 1509","He was wounded by a poisoned arrow during a return trip to Florida in 1521 and died shortly after"]},"Kaiser Wilhelm II":{"desc":"Kaiser Wilhelm II was the last emperor of Germany, ruling from 1888 until he was forced to give up the throne at the end of World War I in 1918. His aggressive foreign policies and military buildup helped set the stage for World War I, one of the deadliest conflicts in history.","facts":["He was the grandson of Britain's Queen Victoria","He dismissed the famous Chancellor Otto von Bismarck in 1890, just two years after becoming Kaiser","He abdicated on November 9, 1918, and fled to the Netherlands, where he lived in exile until his death in 1941"]},"Kim dynasty":{"desc":"The Kim dynasty refers to the family that has ruled North Korea since the country was founded in 1948. Three generations of the Kim family have been supreme leaders, making North Korea the world's only communist country with a hereditary succession of power.","facts":["Kim Il-sung founded North Korea in 1948 and ruled until his death in 1994; he is still officially called the 'Eternal President'","Kim Jong-il succeeded his father and ruled from 1994 to 2011, overseeing North Korea's first nuclear weapons tests","Kim Jong-un took power in 2011 at about age 27, becoming one of the world's youngest heads of state"]},"L'Anse aux Meadows":{"desc":"L'Anse aux Meadows is an archaeological site at the northern tip of the island of Newfoundland in Canada where Norse (Viking) explorers built a settlement around the year 1000 AD. This is the only confirmed Viking settlement in North America and proves that Europeans reached the Americas about 500 years before Christopher Columbus.","facts":["The site was discovered in 1960 by Norwegian explorers Helge and Anne Stine Ingstad","It dates to around 1000 AD, nearly 500 years before Columbus's 1492 voyage","It became a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1978 and contains the remains of eight Norse buildings including a forge"]},"Lakota":{"desc":"The Lakota are a Native American people who are part of the larger Sioux nation and have lived on the Great Plains for hundreds of years. They were skilled buffalo hunters and fierce warriors who fought to protect their homeland from U.S. expansion.","facts":["Famous Lakota leaders include Sitting Bull, Crazy Horse, and Red Cloud","The Lakota won a major victory at the Battle of the Little Bighorn in 1876","The Wounded Knee Massacre on December 29, 1890, in South Dakota killed around 250-300 Lakota men, women, and children"]},"Library of Alexandria":{"desc":"The Library of Alexandria was the most famous library in the ancient world, located in Alexandria, Egypt. It was founded around 300 BC and tried to collect copies of every book in the world, making it the greatest center of learning and knowledge in ancient times.","facts":["It was founded around 295 BC by Ptolemy I Soter, one of Alexander the Great's generals, and may have contained up to 400,000 scrolls","Scholars at the library included Euclid (who wrote about geometry), Eratosthenes (who calculated the Earth's circumference), and Archimedes","The library was gradually destroyed over several centuries, not in a single dramatic fire, with the final destruction likely occurring around 391 AD"]},"Little Big Horn":{"desc":"The Battle of the Little Bighorn, fought on June 25-26, 1876, in Montana, was a major battle between the U.S. Army and a combined force of Lakota, Northern Cheyenne, and Arapaho warriors. It is also known as 'Custer's Last Stand' because Lieutenant Colonel George Armstrong Custer and all of his men in his immediate command were killed.","facts":["Custer's 7th Cavalry force of about 210 soldiers was wiped out","The Native American forces were led by Sitting Bull and Crazy Horse","It was the worst U.S. Army defeat during the Plains Indian Wars"]},"Lorraine Motel":{"desc":"The Lorraine Motel in Memphis, Tennessee, is the place where civil rights leader Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. was assassinated on April 4, 1968. The motel has been preserved and is now part of the National Civil Rights Museum.","facts":["King was shot while standing on the second-floor balcony of room 306","James Earl Ray was convicted of the assassination and sentenced to 99 years in prison","The National Civil Rights Museum opened at the site on September 28, 1991"]},"Louvre":{"desc":"The Louvre is the world's largest and most visited art museum, located in Paris, France. It was originally built as a fortress in the 12th century, later became a royal palace, and was turned into a public museum during the French Revolution in 1793.","facts":["The Louvre is home to the Mona Lisa by Leonardo da Vinci and the ancient Greek statue Venus de Milo","The museum has about 380,000 objects and displays around 35,000 works of art","The famous glass pyramid entrance was designed by architect I.M. Pei and opened in 1989"]},"Lyndon B. Johnson":{"desc":"Lyndon B. Johnson, often called LBJ, was the 36th President of the United States, serving from 1963 to 1969. He became president after John F. Kennedy was assassinated and is known for his 'Great Society' programs and for signing major civil rights laws.","facts":["He signed the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and the Voting Rights Act of 1965","He was sworn in as president aboard Air Force One just hours after Kennedy's assassination on November 22, 1963","He chose not to run for re-election in 1968, partly because of growing opposition to the Vietnam War"]},"Macbeth":{"desc":"Macbeth was a real King of Scotland who ruled from 1040 to 1057, though he is much more famous as a character in William Shakespeare's play. The real Macbeth killed King Duncan I in battle to take the throne, and he actually ruled Scotland fairly well for 17 years before being defeated himself.","facts":["The real Macbeth ruled Scotland from 1040 to 1057","Shakespeare wrote his play Macbeth around 1606, partly to please King James I, who was interested in Scottish history","Macbeth was killed at the Battle of Lumphanan on August 15, 1057, by forces loyal to Duncan's son Malcolm"]},"Madagascar":{"desc":"Madagascar is the fourth-largest island in the world, located off the southeast coast of Africa in the Indian Ocean. It has been isolated from the mainland for millions of years, so about 90% of its plants and animals, including the famous lemurs, are found nowhere else on Earth.","facts":["The first humans arrived on Madagascar around 350-550 AD, believed to be Austronesian sailors from Southeast Asia, over 3,000 miles away","The island became a unified kingdom under King Andrianampoinimerina and his son Radama I in the early 1800s","Madagascar was a French colony from 1897 until it gained independence on June 26, 1960"]},"Mandate of Heaven":{"desc":"The Mandate of Heaven was an important idea in Chinese history that said the right to rule came from heaven, and that a ruler who was unjust or incompetent would lose that right. This concept was used for thousands of years to explain why dynasties rose and fell in China.","facts":["The concept was first used by the Zhou Dynasty around 1046 BC to justify overthrowing the Shang Dynasty","Natural disasters like floods, famines, and earthquakes were seen as signs that a ruler had lost the Mandate of Heaven","Unlike the European 'divine right of kings,' the Mandate of Heaven could be taken away from a bad ruler and given to someone else"]},"Marie Antoinette":{"desc":"Marie Antoinette was the Queen of France and wife of King Louis XVI during the French Revolution. She became a symbol of royal excess and was deeply unpopular with the French people, and she was eventually executed by guillotine during the Revolution.","facts":["She was born an Austrian princess on November 2, 1755, and married the future Louis XVI at age 14","She was executed by guillotine on October 16, 1793, during the French Revolution","The famous quote 'Let them eat cake' is often attributed to her, but historians believe she never actually said it"]},"Mark Antony":{"desc":"Mark Antony was a powerful Roman general and politician who was a loyal follower of Julius Caesar and later became one of the rulers of the Roman Republic. He is famous for his love affair with Cleopatra, the queen of Egypt, and for his war against Octavian (the future Emperor Augustus) that ended the Roman Republic.","facts":["He gave a famous funeral speech for Julius Caesar in 44 BC that turned the Roman people against Caesar's assassins","He formed the Second Triumvirate with Octavian and Lepidus in 43 BC to rule the Roman Republic","He and Cleopatra were defeated by Octavian at the Battle of Actium in 31 BC, and both committed suicide in 30 BC"]},"Mary Cassatt":{"desc":"Mary Cassatt was an American artist who lived and worked in Paris, France, and became one of the few women in the Impressionist art movement. She was especially known for her tender paintings and pastels of mothers and children, and she helped bring Impressionist art to American collectors.","facts":["She was born on May 22, 1844, in Allegheny City, Pennsylvania","She was invited to exhibit with the French Impressionists by Edgar Degas in 1877","She helped her American friends, including the Havemeyers, build major art collections that were later donated to the Metropolitan Museum of Art"]},"Mayor of the Palace":{"desc":"The Mayor of the Palace was originally a household manager for the Frankish kings but over time became the real power behind the throne. The most famous Mayors of the Palace were the Carolingian family, who eventually overthrew the weak Merovingian kings and took the crown for themselves.","facts":["Charles Martel, a Mayor of the Palace, defeated a Muslim army at the Battle of Tours in 732, stopping the Islamic expansion into Western Europe","Pepin the Short, son of Charles Martel, became the first Carolingian king in 751 by deposing the last Merovingian king","The position existed in the Frankish kingdoms from the 6th to 8th centuries, and the later Merovingian kings were so powerless they were called 'do-nothing kings'"]},"Menelik II":{"desc":"Menelik II was the Emperor of Ethiopia from 1889 to 1913 and is best known for defeating an Italian invasion at the Battle of Adwa in 1896. This victory made Ethiopia one of the only African countries to successfully resist European colonization during the Scramble for Africa.","facts":["He defeated the Italian army at the Battle of Adwa on March 1, 1896, with a force of about 100,000 Ethiopian soldiers","He modernized Ethiopia by introducing electricity, telephones, railways, and a postal system","He founded Addis Ababa as his capital in 1886, and it remains the capital of Ethiopia today"]},"Milton Friedman":{"desc":"Milton Friedman was an American economist who believed strongly in free markets and limited government involvement in the economy. His ideas were very influential in the 20th century and shaped economic policies in the United States, the United Kingdom, and many other countries.","facts":["He won the Nobel Prize in Economics in 1976","He was a professor at the University of Chicago for 30 years, from 1946 to 1976","His ideas influenced British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and U.S. President Ronald Reagan"]},"Moai":{"desc":"Moai are the giant stone statues found on Easter Island (Rapa Nui) in the Pacific Ocean, which belongs to Chile. The Rapa Nui people carved nearly 900 of these huge figures between about 1250 and 1500 AD to honor their ancestors.","facts":["There are 887 known moai statues on Easter Island","The largest moai ever erected is about 33 feet tall and weighs around 82 tons","The statues were carved from volcanic rock at the Rano Raraku quarry"]},"Mobutu Sese Seko":{"desc":"Mobutu Sese Seko was the dictator of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (which he renamed Zaire) for 32 years, from 1965 to 1997. He came to power in a military coup and became one of Africa's most corrupt leaders, stealing billions of dollars from his own country while his people lived in poverty.","facts":["He seized power in a CIA-backed coup in 1965 and renamed the country Zaire in 1971","He is estimated to have stolen between $4 and $5 billion from Zaire, equivalent to the country's entire national debt","He was overthrown by rebel leader Laurent-Desire Kabila in 1997 and died in exile in Morocco four months later"]},"Mount Vesuvius":{"desc":"Mount Vesuvius is a volcano near Naples, Italy, that is most famous for its eruption in 79 AD, which buried the Roman cities of Pompeii and Herculaneum under volcanic ash and rock. It is one of the most dangerous volcanoes in the world because about three million people live near it today.","facts":["The 79 AD eruption killed an estimated 16,000 people and buried Pompeii under about 20 feet of volcanic ash","The eruption was described in detail by Pliny the Younger, whose uncle Pliny the Elder died trying to rescue people","Vesuvius has erupted more than 50 times since 79 AD, with the most recent eruption occurring in 1944 during World War II"]},"Muammar Gaddafi":{"desc":"Muammar Gaddafi was the leader of Libya for 42 years, from 1969 to 2011, making him one of the longest-ruling non-royal leaders in history. He took power in a military coup at age 27 and ruled Libya with an unusual political system he described in his 'Green Book' until he was overthrown and killed during the Arab Spring.","facts":["He seized power from King Idris in a bloodless military coup on September 1, 1969, when he was just 27 years old","He was linked to the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988, which killed 270 people","He was captured and killed by rebel fighters on October 20, 2011, during the Libyan Civil War that was part of the Arab Spring"]},"Muhammad Yunus":{"desc":"Muhammad Yunus is a Bangladeshi economist who invented the idea of microcredit, which means giving very small loans to poor people so they can start businesses. His work has helped millions of people around the world escape poverty, and he won the Nobel Peace Prize in 2006.","facts":["He won the Nobel Peace Prize in 2006, shared with the Grameen Bank he founded","He started microlending in 1976 by personally lending $27 to 42 women in a village in Bangladesh","He has been called the 'banker to the poor' and his ideas have spread to more than 100 countries"]},"Musket Wars":{"desc":"The Musket Wars were a series of battles fought between Maori tribes in New Zealand from about 1807 to 1845, after some tribes got muskets (guns) from European traders. Tribes with muskets attacked tribes that did not have them, causing huge changes in where different Maori groups lived across New Zealand.","facts":["An estimated 20,000 to 40,000 Maori were killed during the Musket Wars","The northern Ngapuhi tribe, led by chief Hongi Hika, was among the first to acquire large numbers of muskets from European traders","The wars caused massive migrations as defeated tribes were forced to move to new territories across New Zealand"]},"Nancy Reagan":{"desc":"Nancy Reagan was the First Lady of the United States from 1981 to 1989, married to President Ronald Reagan. She is best known for her 'Just Say No' anti-drug campaign aimed at young people.","facts":["She was born on July 6, 1921, in New York City, and her birth name was Anne Frances Robbins","Before entering politics, she was a Hollywood actress in the 1940s and 1950s","She passed away on March 6, 2016, at age 94"]},"Neville Chamberlain":{"desc":"Neville Chamberlain was the British Prime Minister who is best remembered for his policy of appeasement toward Adolf Hitler before World War II. He signed the Munich Agreement in 1938, allowing Germany to take part of Czechoslovakia, and famously declared it meant 'peace for our time,' but war broke out less than a year later.","facts":["He served as Prime Minister of the United Kingdom from 1937 to 1940","He signed the Munich Agreement on September 30, 1938, giving Hitler the Sudetenland region of Czechoslovakia","He resigned as Prime Minister on May 10, 1940, and was replaced by Winston Churchill"]},"Ninety-five Theses":{"desc":"The Ninety-five Theses were a list of arguments written by Martin Luther in 1517 that criticized the Catholic Church for selling indulgences (pardons for sins). This document helped start the Protestant Reformation, which changed Christianity and European history forever.","facts":["Martin Luther posted the Ninety-five Theses on October 31, 1517, in Wittenberg, Germany","The main complaint was about the sale of indulgences, especially by a friar named Johann Tetzel","The Theses helped spark the Protestant Reformation, leading to new Christian denominations like Lutheranism"]},"Nineveh":{"desc":"Nineveh was the great capital of the ancient Assyrian Empire, located on the banks of the Tigris River in what is now Mosul, Iraq. At its peak it was one of the largest and most magnificent cities in the entire ancient world, but it was completely destroyed in 612 BC.","facts":["King Sennacherib made Nineveh the Assyrian capital around 705 BC and built a massive palace with over 70 rooms","The city walls were about 7.5 miles (12 km) long with 15 gates, and the city may have had a population of over 100,000","King Ashurbanipal's library at Nineveh contained over 30,000 clay tablets, including the Epic of Gilgamesh, one of the oldest known works of literature"]},"Osama bin Laden":{"desc":"Osama bin Laden was the founder and leader of al-Qaeda, the terrorist organization responsible for the September 11, 2001, attacks on the United States that killed nearly 3,000 people. He was one of the most wanted fugitives in the world for nearly a decade.","facts":["He was born in 1957 in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, to a wealthy family","He was found and killed by U.S. Navy SEALs in a raid on his compound in Abbottabad, Pakistan, on May 2, 2011","The operation to find and eliminate him was code-named Operation Neptune Spear"]},"Parliament Act of 1911":{"desc":"The Parliament Act of 1911 was an important British law that greatly reduced the power of the House of Lords, the unelected upper chamber of Parliament. It meant that the elected House of Commons would have the final say on laws, especially about money and taxes.","facts":["It removed the House of Lords' power to veto money bills entirely","It limited the Lords' ability to delay other bills to a maximum of two years (later reduced to one year in 1949)","It also reduced the maximum length of a Parliament from seven years to five years"]},"Parson Weems":{"desc":"Mason Locke Weems, known as Parson Weems, was an American author and book seller who wrote a famous biography of George Washington shortly after Washington's death. He is best known for inventing the story of young George Washington chopping down a cherry tree.","facts":["His book, The Life of Washington, was first published in 1800","The famous cherry tree story first appeared in the fifth edition of his book in 1806","He was called 'Parson' because he was an ordained minister of the Episcopal Church"]},"Parthenon":{"desc":"The Parthenon is a famous ancient Greek temple built on top of the Acropolis hill in Athens, dedicated to the goddess Athena. It was built between 447 and 432 BC and is considered one of the greatest examples of ancient Greek architecture ever created.","facts":["It was built between 447 and 432 BC under the leadership of Pericles, with architects Ictinus and Callicrates","The original Parthenon contained a 40-foot-tall gold and ivory statue of Athena created by the sculptor Phidias","Many of the Parthenon's marble sculptures, known as the Elgin Marbles, were removed by Lord Elgin in the early 1800s and are now in the British Museum"]},"Petticoat Affair":{"desc":"The Petticoat Affair was a scandal during President Andrew Jackson's administration in 1829-1831 involving Peggy Eaton, the wife of Secretary of War John Eaton. The wives of other Cabinet members refused to socialize with Peggy because of rumors about her past, which caused a big political conflict.","facts":["The scandal led to the resignation of nearly the entire Cabinet in 1831","Vice President John C. Calhoun's wife was one of the leaders of the social snubbing against Peggy Eaton","Secretary of State Martin Van Buren supported the Eatons, which helped him gain Jackson's favor and eventually become vice president and then president"]},"Philip II":{"desc":"Philip II was the King of Macedon from 359 to 336 BC and the father of Alexander the Great. He transformed Macedonia from a weak kingdom into the most powerful military force in Greece, conquering most of the Greek city-states and laying the groundwork for his son's vast empire.","facts":["He created the Macedonian phalanx, a powerful military formation using long spears called sarissas that were 18-20 feet long","He defeated the Greek city-states at the Battle of Chaeronea in 338 BC, gaining control over most of Greece","He was assassinated in 336 BC by one of his own bodyguards, Pausanias, at his daughter's wedding"]},"Pizarro":{"desc":"Francisco Pizarro was a Spanish conquistador who conquered the Inca Empire in South America in the 1530s. With only about 168 men, he captured the Inca emperor Atahualpa and took control of one of the largest empires in the world.","facts":["Pizarro captured the Inca emperor Atahualpa at the Battle of Cajamarca in 1532","He founded the city of Lima, Peru, in 1535","He was assassinated by rivals in Lima on June 26, 1541"]},"Plymouth Colony":{"desc":"Plymouth Colony was founded in 1620 by English settlers known as the Pilgrims, who sailed across the Atlantic Ocean on the Mayflower. It was one of the earliest successful English settlements in North America, located in present-day Massachusetts.","facts":["The Pilgrims signed the Mayflower Compact before landing, which was an early form of self-government","The first Thanksgiving was celebrated in the fall of 1621 between the Pilgrims and the Wampanoag people","Plymouth Colony merged with the Massachusetts Bay Colony in 1691"]},"Pocahontas":{"desc":"Pocahontas was a Native American woman of the Powhatan nation who played an important role in the early days of the English settlement at Jamestown, Virginia. She is famous for her connection to Captain John Smith and for helping maintain peace between her people and the English colonists.","facts":["Her real name was Amonute, and Pocahontas was a childhood nickname meaning 'playful one'","She married English colonist John Rolfe in 1614, which helped create a period of peace between the colonists and the Powhatan","She traveled to England in 1616 but died there in March 1617 at about age 21"]},"Politburo":{"desc":"The Politburo was the top decision-making group in the Communist Party of the Soviet Union and the most powerful political body in the country. Its small group of members, usually around 10 to 15 people, made all the major decisions about running the Soviet Union.","facts":["The Politburo was first created in 1917 during the Russian Revolution","Famous Politburo members included Joseph Stalin, Nikita Khrushchev, and Leonid Brezhnev","The Politburo was dissolved in 1991 when the Soviet Union collapsed"]},"Polyphemus":{"desc":"Polyphemus is a famous one-eyed giant called a Cyclops from Greek mythology, most well-known from Homer's epic poem the Odyssey. In the story, he trapped the hero Odysseus and his men in his cave and ate several of them before Odysseus came up with a clever plan to escape.","facts":["In the Odyssey, Odysseus blinded Polyphemus by driving a sharpened wooden stake into his single eye","Odysseus told Polyphemus his name was 'Nobody,' so when Polyphemus cried for help, the other Cyclopes thought nobody was hurting him","Polyphemus was the son of Poseidon, god of the sea, and Poseidon punished Odysseus for blinding his son by making his journey home take 10 years"]},"Pompeii":{"desc":"Pompeii was an ancient Roman city near Naples, Italy, that was buried under volcanic ash when Mount Vesuvius erupted in 79 AD. The ash preserved the city almost perfectly for nearly 1,700 years, giving us an amazing snapshot of what daily life was like in the Roman Empire.","facts":["The city was rediscovered in 1748 and has been one of the most important archaeological sites in the world ever since","About 2,000 people died in Pompeii, many preserved as plaster casts showing their final moments","The preserved city includes homes, shops, baths, theaters, and even graffiti, giving historians an incredibly detailed look at Roman life"]},"Princess Diana":{"desc":"Princess Diana was a member of the British royal family who married Prince Charles in 1981 and became one of the most famous and beloved people in the world. She was known for her charity work, especially with children and people affected by AIDS and landmines, and her tragic death in 1997 shocked the world.","facts":["She married Prince Charles on July 29, 1981, in a ceremony watched by 750 million TV viewers worldwide","She died in a car crash in Paris on August 31, 1997, at the age of 36","She was the mother of Prince William and Prince Harry"]},"Prussia":{"desc":"Prussia was a powerful German kingdom that played the leading role in unifying the many German states into one country, the German Empire, in 1871. For centuries, Prussia was known for its strong military and disciplined government, and it dominated German politics until it was dissolved after World War II.","facts":["Otto von Bismarck, the Prussian Prime Minister, unified Germany in 1871 and became its first Chancellor","Prussia's capital was Berlin, which also became the capital of the German Empire","Prussia was officially dissolved by the Allied powers in 1947 after World War II"]},"Quiet Revolution":{"desc":"The Quiet Revolution was a period of rapid social and political change in the Canadian province of Quebec during the 1960s. French-speaking Quebecers modernized their society, reduced the Catholic Church's influence, and pushed for more recognition of French Canadian culture and language.","facts":["It began around 1960 when the Quebec Liberal Party under Jean Lesage won the provincial election","The Quebec government took control of education and healthcare from the Catholic Church","It led to a growing movement for Quebec sovereignty, including a 1980 referendum on independence that was defeated"]},"RMS Lusitania":{"desc":"The RMS Lusitania was a large British ocean liner that was sunk by a German submarine during World War I, killing nearly 1,200 people. The sinking outraged people around the world, especially in the United States, and helped push America closer to joining the war against Germany.","facts":["It was torpedoed by German U-boat U-20 on May 7, 1915, off the coast of Ireland","1,198 people died, including 128 Americans","The ship sank in just 18 minutes after being hit"]},"Ray Kroc":{"desc":"Ray Kroc was an American businessman who turned McDonald's from a small restaurant in California into the world's largest fast-food chain. He bought the franchise rights from the McDonald brothers and built it into a global empire.","facts":["He opened his first McDonald's franchise in Des Plaines, Illinois, on April 15, 1955","He was 52 years old and working as a milkshake mixer salesman when he discovered the McDonald brothers' restaurant","He also owned the San Diego Padres baseball team from 1974 until his death in 1984"]},"Renaissance":{"desc":"The Renaissance was a period of great cultural and artistic achievement that began in Italy around the 1300s and spread across Europe over the next few centuries. It means 'rebirth' in French, and it was a time when people became excited about learning, art, science, and the ideas of ancient Greece and Rome.","facts":["It began in Italian city-states like Florence, Venice, and Rome in the 14th century","Famous Renaissance artists include Leonardo da Vinci, Michelangelo, and Raphael","Johannes Gutenberg's invention of the printing press around 1440 helped spread Renaissance ideas across Europe"]},"René Descartes":{"desc":"René Descartes was a French philosopher, mathematician, and scientist who is often called the 'Father of Modern Philosophy.' He is famous for his statement 'I think, therefore I am,' and he also invented the coordinate system used in math class today.","facts":["He was born on March 31, 1596, in La Haye en Touraine, France","He wrote his famous philosophical work Meditations on First Philosophy in 1641","The Cartesian coordinate system (the x-y grid used in math) is named after him"]},"Rishi Sunak":{"desc":"Rishi Sunak became the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom in October 2022, making him the first British leader of Indian heritage and the youngest PM in over 200 years. Before becoming Prime Minister, he served as Chancellor of the Exchequer, managing the country's finances during the COVID-19 pandemic.","facts":["He became Prime Minister on October 25, 2022, at the age of 42","He was the first Hindu and first person of South Asian descent to serve as UK Prime Minister","He previously served as Chancellor of the Exchequer from February 2020 to July 2022"]},"Rolling Stones":{"desc":"The Rolling Stones are a legendary British rock band formed in London in 1962, known for their energetic music and live performances. Along with The Beatles, they are considered one of the most important and influential bands in the history of rock and roll.","facts":["The band was formed in London in 1962 by Mick Jagger, Keith Richards, and Brian Jones","Their hit songs include 'Satisfaction,' 'Paint It Black,' and 'Sympathy for the Devil'","They are one of the best-selling music artists of all time, with over 200 million records sold worldwide"]},"Romulus and Remus":{"desc":"Romulus and Remus were the legendary twin brothers who founded the city of Rome in 753 BCE, according to Roman mythology. They were said to have been raised by a she-wolf after being abandoned as babies. Romulus killed Remus in a dispute and became the first King of Rome.","facts":["Legendary twin founders of Rome in 753 BCE","Said to have been raised by a she-wolf","Romulus killed Remus and became Rome's first king","The city of Rome is named after Romulus","One of the most important founding myths in Western civilization"]},"Russo-Ukrainian War":{"desc":"The Russo-Ukrainian War began in 2014 when Russia annexed Crimea from Ukraine and supported separatist fighters in eastern Ukraine. The conflict dramatically escalated on February 24, 2022, when Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine, leading to one of the largest wars in Europe since World War II.","facts":["Russia annexed the Crimean Peninsula from Ukraine in March 2014","Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine on February 24, 2022","The war has caused millions of Ukrainians to flee their homes as refugees to neighboring countries"]},"Second Triumvirate":{"desc":"The Second Triumvirate was an official alliance formed in 43 BC by three powerful Roman leaders: Octavian (Julius Caesar's adopted son), Mark Antony, and Lepidus. They joined forces to defeat Caesar's assassins and rule the Roman Republic, but they eventually turned on each other in a power struggle.","facts":["It was formally established by the Lex Titia on November 27, 43 BC, giving the three men dictatorial powers for five years","They created proscription lists that led to the execution of about 300 senators and 2,000 equestrians, including the famous orator Cicero","The alliance ended when Octavian defeated Antony at the Battle of Actium in 31 BC and became the sole ruler of Rome as Emperor Augustus"]},"Sequoyah":{"desc":"Sequoyah was a Cherokee silversmith and scholar who created a written system for the Cherokee language, known as a syllabary, in 1821. This was one of the only times in history that a person who could not read or write in any language created a complete writing system.","facts":["His syllabary had 85 characters, each representing a syllable in the Cherokee language","Within a few years of its introduction, most Cherokee people could read and write in their own language","The giant sequoia trees of California were named in his honor"]},"Seven Wonders of the Ancient World":{"desc":"The Seven Wonders of the Ancient World were a list of the most impressive buildings and structures known to ancient Greek travelers and historians. Of the seven wonders, only one still exists today: the Great Pyramid of Giza in Egypt, which is also the oldest of the seven.","facts":["The seven wonders are: the Great Pyramid of Giza, the Hanging Gardens of Babylon, the Statue of Zeus at Olympia, the Temple of Artemis at Ephesus, the Mausoleum at Halicarnassus, the Colossus of Rhodes, and the Lighthouse of Alexandria","The Great Pyramid of Giza, built around 2560 BC, is the only wonder still standing today","The Colossus of Rhodes, a giant bronze statue about 108 feet tall, stood for only 54 years before being destroyed by an earthquake in 226 BC"]},"Silk Road":{"desc":"The Silk Road was a network of ancient trade routes connecting China to the Mediterranean world, stretching over 4,000 miles. It was used from about the 2nd century BCE to the 15th century CE to trade silk, spices, gems, and ideas between East and West. The routes also spread religions like Buddhism, Islam, and Christianity.","facts":["Network of trade routes connecting China to the Mediterranean","Named for the valuable Chinese silk traded along it","Active from about the 2nd century BCE to the 15th century CE","Spread goods, ideas, religions, and even diseases like the Black Plague","Marco Polo traveled along the Silk Road to reach China"]},"Smoot-Hawley Act":{"desc":"The Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act was a law passed in 1930 that raised tariffs (taxes) on over 20,000 imported goods to some of the highest levels in U.S. history. Many economists believe it made the Great Depression worse by starting trade wars with other countries.","facts":["It was sponsored by Senator Reed Smoot of Utah and Representative Willis C. Hawley of Oregon","President Herbert Hoover signed it into law on June 17, 1930, despite a petition signed by over 1,000 economists urging him not to","Other countries retaliated with their own tariffs, and world trade dropped by about 65% between 1929 and 1934"]},"Socrates":{"desc":"Socrates was an ancient Greek philosopher from Athens who lived from about 470 to 399 BCE. He is considered the founder of Western philosophy and developed the Socratic method of questioning. He was sentenced to death by drinking hemlock, accused of corrupting the youth of Athens.","facts":["Ancient Greek philosopher (c. 470-399 BCE)","Considered the founder of Western philosophy","Developed the Socratic method of teaching through questions","Never wrote anything down - known through writings of his student Plato","Executed by drinking hemlock in 399 BCE"]},"Space shuttles":{"desc":"The Space Shuttle was NASA's reusable spacecraft that carried astronauts and cargo into space from 1981 to 2011. There were five operational shuttles, and they completed 135 missions over 30 years of service.","facts":["The five shuttles were Columbia, Challenger, Discovery, Atlantis, and Endeavour","The Challenger disaster on January 28, 1986, and the Columbia disaster on February 1, 2003, each killed all seven crew members aboard","The first shuttle mission was flown by Columbia on April 12, 1981"]},"Stephen A. Douglas":{"desc":"Stephen A. Douglas was a U.S. Senator from Illinois who is famous for his series of debates with Abraham Lincoln in 1858 and for championing the idea of popular sovereignty, which let territories decide for themselves whether to allow slavery. He was known as the 'Little Giant' because he was short but a powerful speaker.","facts":["He debated Abraham Lincoln seven times during the 1858 Illinois Senate race, and Douglas won that election","He proposed the Kansas-Nebraska Act of 1854, which repealed the Missouri Compromise","He ran against Lincoln for president in 1860 but lost, then supported Lincoln and the Union cause before dying in 1861"]},"String Quartet":{"desc":"A string quartet is a group of four musicians who play together using two violins, one viola, and one cello. This type of music group became very popular in Europe during the 1700s, and famous composers like Mozart, Beethoven, and Haydn wrote some of their greatest music for string quartets.","facts":["Joseph Haydn is called the 'Father of the String Quartet' and wrote 68 of them","Ludwig van Beethoven wrote 16 string quartets, which are considered some of the greatest chamber music ever composed","The standard string quartet format of two violins, viola, and cello was established in the mid-1700s"]},"Suleiman the Magnificent":{"desc":"Suleiman the Magnificent was the longest-reigning Sultan of the Ottoman Empire, ruling from 1520 to 1566. Under his leadership, the Ottoman Empire reached its greatest size and power, stretching across three continents and becoming one of the most powerful empires in the world.","facts":["He ruled for 46 years, from 1520 to 1566, the longest reign of any Ottoman Sultan","He besieged Vienna in 1529, reaching the furthest point of Ottoman expansion into Europe","He was known in the Islamic world as 'The Lawgiver' because he reformed the Ottoman legal system"]},"Suriname":{"desc":"Suriname is a small country on the northeastern coast of South America that used to be a Dutch colony. It is the smallest country in South America and is one of the few places in the Americas where Dutch is the official language.","facts":["Suriname gained independence from the Netherlands on November 25, 1975","It is the smallest country in South America by area","Dutch is the official language, making it unique in South America"]},"Taiping Rebellion":{"desc":"The Taiping Rebellion was a massive civil war in China from 1850 to 1864, led by Hong Xiuquan, who believed he was the brother of Jesus Christ. It was one of the deadliest conflicts in human history, killing an estimated 20 to 30 million people, far more than many world wars.","facts":["An estimated 20 to 30 million people died, making it one of the deadliest wars in human history","The leader, Hong Xiuquan, claimed he was the younger brother of Jesus Christ and established the Taiping Heavenly Kingdom","The rebellion was finally defeated with help from European-led armies like the Ever Victorious Army commanded by Charles Gordon"]},"Tamil Tigers":{"desc":"The Tamil Tigers were a rebel group in Sri Lanka that fought for an independent homeland for the Tamil people in the north and east of the island. They fought a brutal civil war against the Sri Lankan government from 1983 to 2009, using many controversial tactics including suicide bombings.","facts":["Their official name was the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), founded by Velupillai Prabhakaran in 1976","They pioneered the use of suicide bombing as a military tactic, carrying out over 300 suicide attacks","The Sri Lankan military defeated them in May 2009, ending a 26-year civil war that killed an estimated 80,000 to 100,000 people"]},"Taoism":{"desc":"Taoism (also called Daoism) is an ancient Chinese religion and philosophy founded by Laozi around the 6th century BC. It teaches people to live in harmony with the Tao, which means 'the Way,' and emphasizes living simply and peacefully with nature.","facts":["Laozi (Lao Tzu) is the traditional founder, and he wrote the key text called the 'Tao Te Ching'","The yin-yang symbol represents the Taoist idea of balance between opposite forces","Taoism began in China and has influenced Chinese culture for over 2,000 years"]},"The Beatles":{"desc":"The Beatles were a British rock band from Liverpool, England, who became the most popular and influential band in music history. Their creative songs and cultural impact in the 1960s changed music forever, and they are the best-selling music act of all time.","facts":["The four members were John Lennon, Paul McCartney, George Harrison, and Ringo Starr","They arrived in New York on February 7, 1964, starting 'Beatlemania' in America","They have sold over 600 million records worldwide, more than any other music act"]},"The Hague":{"desc":"The Hague is a city in the Netherlands that serves as the seat of the Dutch government and is known as the international capital of justice. Many important international courts and organizations are located there, making it a key center for international law and diplomacy.","facts":["The International Court of Justice, the main judicial body of the United Nations, is located in The Hague","The International Criminal Court, which prosecutes war crimes, is also based there","Although Amsterdam is the official capital of the Netherlands, the government and parliament sit in The Hague"]},"The North Star":{"desc":"The North Star was an anti-slavery newspaper started by Frederick Douglass in Rochester, New York, in 1847. It was named after the star that enslaved people used to guide them north to freedom and became one of the most important abolitionist publications.","facts":["The first issue was published on December 3, 1847","Its motto was 'Right is of no Sex — Truth is of no Color — God is the Father of us all, and we are all brethren'","The paper merged with the Liberty Party Paper in 1851 and became Frederick Douglass' Paper"]},"The Odyssey":{"desc":"The Odyssey is an ancient Greek epic poem written by Homer around 700 BC that tells the story of the hero Odysseus trying to get home after the Trojan War. His journey takes ten years and is full of incredible adventures, including encounters with monsters, gods, and magical creatures.","facts":["The Odyssey was written by the Greek poet Homer around 700 BC","The hero Odysseus takes 10 years to return home to Ithaca after the Trojan War","Famous episodes include encounters with the Cyclops Polyphemus, the witch Circe, and the Sirens"]},"The Three Musketeers":{"desc":"The Three Musketeers is a famous adventure novel written by French author Alexandre Dumas and published in 1844. It tells the exciting story of a young man named d'Artagnan who joins three musketeers — Athos, Porthos, and Aramis — in service to the King of France.","facts":["The novel was written by Alexandre Dumas and first published in serial form in 1844","The story is set in France during the 1620s, during the reign of King Louis XIII","The musketeers' famous motto is 'All for one and one for all'"]},"Thermopylae":{"desc":"Thermopylae is a narrow mountain pass in central Greece where one of the most famous battles in history took place in 480 BC. A small force of Greek soldiers, led by King Leonidas of Sparta with his 300 Spartan warriors, held off a massive Persian army for three days before being defeated.","facts":["King Leonidas led about 7,000 Greek soldiers, including 300 Spartans, against a Persian army estimated at 100,000 to 300,000","The Greeks held the narrow pass for three days until a local traitor named Ephialtes showed the Persians a secret mountain path to get behind them","Leonidas and his 300 Spartans stayed behind to fight to the death, allowing the rest of the Greek army to retreat"]},"Three Sisters":{"desc":"The Three Sisters refers to the three main crops grown together by many Native American tribes: corn, beans, and squash. These crops were planted together because they help each other grow — the corn provides a stalk for the beans to climb, the beans add nitrogen to the soil, and the squash leaves shade the ground to keep moisture in.","facts":["This farming method was used by the Iroquois, Cherokee, and many other Native American groups for hundreds of years","The three crops together provide a nutritionally balanced diet with carbohydrates, protein, and vitamins","The Iroquois considered the Three Sisters to be gifts from the Great Spirit and held ceremonies to celebrate them"]},"Tigris River":{"desc":"The Tigris River is one of the two great rivers of Mesopotamia (the other being the Euphrates), flowing through modern-day Turkey, Syria, and Iraq. Ancient civilizations like the Sumerians, Assyrians, and Babylonians built some of the world's first cities along the Tigris thousands of years ago.","facts":["The Tigris is about 1,150 miles (1,850 km) long, flowing from the mountains of eastern Turkey to the Persian Gulf","The ancient Assyrian capital of Nineveh was located on the banks of the Tigris, near modern-day Mosul, Iraq","Baghdad, founded in 762 AD, was built on the western bank of the Tigris River"]},"Titanomachy":{"desc":"The Titanomachy is the legendary war between the Titans and the Olympian gods in Greek mythology. Led by Zeus, the younger Olympian gods fought against the older Titans led by Kronos for control of the universe, and after ten years of fighting, the Olympians won and became the rulers of the cosmos.","facts":["The war lasted ten years, according to the Greek poet Hesiod's Theogony, written around 700 BC","Zeus freed the Cyclopes and the Hundred-Handed Ones from prison to help fight the Titans","After winning, Zeus imprisoned most of the defeated Titans in Tartarus, a deep pit beneath the underworld"]},"Tony Blair":{"desc":"Tony Blair was the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom from 1997 to 2007 and the leader of the Labour Party. He won three general elections in a row and modernized the Labour Party, but his decision to support the 2003 invasion of Iraq was very controversial.","facts":["He became Prime Minister on May 2, 1997, at the age of 43","He played a key role in the Good Friday Agreement of 1998, which helped bring peace to Northern Ireland","He was the longest-serving Labour Prime Minister, holding office for 10 years"]},"Tutankhamun":{"desc":"Tutankhamun, often called King Tut, was an ancient Egyptian pharaoh who ruled from about 1332 to 1323 BC. He became pharaoh when he was only about 9 years old, and although he was not very important during his lifetime, the discovery of his nearly untouched tomb in 1922 made him the most famous pharaoh in the world.","facts":["He became pharaoh at about age 9 and died at about age 19, possibly from a leg infection combined with malaria","His tomb in the Valley of the Kings was discovered by Howard Carter on November 4, 1922, containing over 5,000 artifacts","His golden death mask, made of about 24 pounds of solid gold, is one of the most recognizable artifacts in the world"]},"Tydings-McDuffie Act":{"desc":"The Tydings-McDuffie Act was a law passed by the United States Congress in 1934 that promised independence to the Philippines after a ten-year transition period. This law set up the process that led to the Philippines becoming a fully independent country on July 4, 1946.","facts":["The act was signed into law on March 24, 1934","It established a 10-year transition period before full Philippine independence","The Philippines officially became independent on July 4, 1946, after the transition was delayed by World War II"]},"U.S. Capitol building":{"desc":"The U.S. Capitol building in Washington, D.C., is where the United States Congress meets to make laws. Its famous dome, topped by the Statue of Freedom, is one of the most recognized symbols of American democracy.","facts":["Construction began on September 18, 1793, when President George Washington laid the cornerstone","The current cast-iron dome was completed during the Civil War in 1866 and weighs about 8.9 million pounds","The building has about 540 rooms and the Rotunda beneath the dome features large paintings of American history"]},"Vandals":{"desc":"The Vandals were a Germanic tribe that migrated across Europe during the fall of the Roman Empire and eventually settled in North Africa. They are most famous for sacking the city of Rome in 455 AD, and their name is the origin of the English word 'vandalism,' meaning the destruction of property.","facts":["They crossed the Rhine River into the Roman Empire on December 31, 406 AD, along with other barbarian tribes","Under King Gaiseric, they conquered Roman North Africa in 439 AD and made Carthage their capital","They sacked Rome for two weeks in June 455 AD, stripping the city of valuables including treasures originally taken from the Temple of Jerusalem"]},"Venezuela":{"desc":"Venezuela is a country on the northern coast of South America that sits on top of some of the world's largest oil reserves. It was one of the first Spanish colonies to fight for independence, led by the famous general Simón Bolívar in the early 1800s.","facts":["Venezuela declared independence from Spain on July 5, 1811","It has the largest proven oil reserves of any country in the world","Simón Bolívar, known as 'The Liberator,' was born in Caracas, Venezuela, in 1783"]},"Volodymyr Zelenskyy":{"desc":"Volodymyr Zelenskyy is the President of Ukraine who became world-famous for his brave leadership after Russia invaded his country in 2022. Before becoming president, he was a comedian and actor who starred in a TV show about a teacher who accidentally becomes president of Ukraine.","facts":["He was elected President of Ukraine on April 21, 2019, winning 73% of the vote","He previously starred in the Ukrainian TV comedy series Servant of the People from 2015 to 2019","He refused offers to leave Kyiv when Russia invaded, reportedly saying he needed ammunition, not a ride"]},"Wales":{"desc":"Wales is a country that is part of the United Kingdom, located on the western side of the island of Great Britain. It has its own language, Welsh, its own culture and traditions, and is known for its beautiful mountains, castles, and rugby teams.","facts":["Wales has over 600 castles, more per square mile than any other country in Europe","The Welsh language, called Cymraeg, is one of the oldest living languages in Europe","Wales was officially united with England by the Laws in Wales Acts of 1535 and 1542"]},"Warren G. Harding":{"desc":"Warren G. Harding was the 29th President of the United States, serving from 1921 until his death in 1923. His presidency is often remembered for the Teapot Dome scandal, one of the biggest corruption scandals in American political history before Watergate.","facts":["He died on August 2, 1923, in San Francisco while on a speaking tour, and was succeeded by Vice President Calvin Coolidge","The Teapot Dome scandal involved his Secretary of the Interior, Albert Fall, who accepted bribes for leasing government oil reserves","He won the 1920 election with over 60% of the popular vote, one of the largest landslides in U.S. history at the time"]},"Wernher von Braun":{"desc":"Wernher von Braun was a German-born rocket engineer who developed the V-2 rocket for Nazi Germany during World War II and later moved to the United States, where he became the key figure in America's space program. He led the team that built the Saturn V rocket, which carried astronauts to the Moon.","facts":["He developed the V-2 rocket for Nazi Germany, the world's first long-range ballistic missile","After the war, he was brought to the United States under Operation Paperclip in 1945","He was the chief architect of the Saturn V rocket that launched the Apollo 11 Moon mission in 1969"]},"William Penn":{"desc":"William Penn was an English Quaker who founded the colony of Pennsylvania in 1681 as a place where people of all religions could worship freely. He treated Native Americans fairly and planned the city of Philadelphia, which became one of the most important cities in colonial America.","facts":["King Charles II granted Penn the charter for Pennsylvania in 1681 to settle a debt owed to Penn's father","Penn founded Philadelphia in 1682, designing it as a grid-pattern city whose name means 'City of Brotherly Love'","He signed a peace treaty with the Lenape (Delaware) Native Americans and was known for treating them with respect"]},"William of Orange":{"desc":"William of Orange, also known as William III, was a Dutch prince who became King of England, Scotland, and Ireland after the Glorious Revolution of 1688. He and his wife Mary II ruled together, and their reign established important principles about the rights of Parliament over the monarchy.","facts":["He was born on November 14, 1650, in The Hague, Netherlands","He and his wife Mary II were crowned as joint monarchs of England on April 11, 1689","He defeated the former King James II at the Battle of the Boyne in Ireland on July 1, 1690"]},"Wimbledon":{"desc":"Wimbledon is the oldest and most prestigious tennis tournament in the world, held every summer in London, England. It is the only Grand Slam tournament still played on grass courts, and it is famous for its traditions like players wearing all white and spectators eating strawberries and cream.","facts":["The first Wimbledon Championship was held in 1877","It is played at the All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club in London","Roger Federer holds the men's record with 8 Wimbledon singles titles, while Martina Navratilova holds the women's record with 9"]},"Wright Brothers":{"desc":"Orville and Wilbur Wright were two American brothers from Dayton, Ohio, who built and flew the first successful powered airplane. Their historic first flight took place on December 17, 1903, at Kitty Hawk, North Carolina.","facts":["The first flight lasted only 12 seconds and covered 120 feet","They made four flights that day, with the longest lasting 59 seconds and covering 852 feet","Before building airplanes, they owned and operated a bicycle repair and sales shop in Dayton, Ohio"]},"Yugoslavia":{"desc":"Yugoslavia was a country in southeastern Europe that existed for most of the 20th century, made up of several different ethnic groups including Serbs, Croats, Bosniaks, and Slovenes. After its leader Tito died in 1980, the country gradually broke apart in a series of violent wars in the 1990s.","facts":["Yugoslavia was created in 1918 after World War I as the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes","It broke apart in the 1990s into six countries: Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Serbia, Montenegro, and North Macedonia","The breakup led to devastating wars, including the Bosnian War (1992–1995) and the Kosovo War (1998–1999)"]},"Zaibatsu":{"desc":"Zaibatsu were huge family-owned business groups that controlled much of Japan's economy from the late 1800s through World War II. These powerful conglomerates owned banks, factories, mines, and shipping companies, and they worked closely with the Japanese government to build Japan into an industrial power.","facts":["The four largest zaibatsu were Mitsubishi, Mitsui, Sumitomo, and Yasuda","After World War II, the American occupation forces broke up the zaibatsu, but many reformed as looser groups called keiretsu","The Mitsui zaibatsu traced its origins back to 1673, making it one of the oldest business enterprises in the world"]},"Zoot Suit Riots":{"desc":"The Zoot Suit Riots were a series of violent clashes in Los Angeles in June 1943 between U.S. servicemen and young Mexican Americans who wore flashy outfits called zoot suits. The riots were fueled by racial tensions and wartime anxieties during World War II.","facts":["The riots lasted from June 3 to June 8, 1943","Servicemen attacked Mexican American, African American, and Filipino American youth, stripping them of their zoot suits and beating them","The Los Angeles City Council banned the wearing of zoot suits during the riots, making it a misdemeanor"]},"India":{"desc":"On August 23, 2023, India's Chandrayaan-3 spacecraft successfully landed on the Moon's south pole, making India only the fourth country to achieve a lunar soft landing (after the Soviet Union, the United States, and China). India was the first country to land near the Moon's south pole. The mission was carried out by ISRO (Indian Space Research Organisation).","facts":["Chandrayaan means 'moon vehicle' in Sanskrit","India's first attempt, Chandrayaan-2, crashed during landing in 2019","The south pole of the Moon is important because it may contain frozen water","The mission cost about $75 million — less than many Hollywood movies","The small rover explored the surface and confirmed the presence of sulfur near the south pole"]},"Jamestown":{"desc":"Jamestown was the first permanent English settlement in North America, founded in 1607 in what is now Virginia. The settlers struggled terribly with starvation and disease, but the colony survived and became the starting point for English colonization of America.","facts":["Jamestown was founded on May 14, 1607, by the Virginia Company of London","Captain John Smith helped lead the colony through its difficult early years","The colony nearly failed during the 'Starving Time' winter of 1609-1610, when most settlers died"]},"Dominican Republic":{"desc":"The Dominican Republic is a Caribbean country that shares the island of Hispaniola with Haiti. It gained independence from Haiti in 1844 and is known for its beautiful beaches, baseball players, and its role as the site where Christopher Columbus first landed in the Americas.","facts":["The Dominican Republic declared independence from Haiti on February 27, 1844","Christopher Columbus arrived on the island of Hispaniola in December 1492","Santo Domingo, its capital, was founded in 1496 and is the oldest European-established city in the Americas"]},"Ecuador":{"desc":"Ecuador is a country in South America named after the equator, which runs right through it. It gained independence from Spain in 1822 with help from the famous generals Simón Bolívar and Antonio José de Sucre.","facts":["Ecuador gained independence from Spain on May 24, 1822, after the Battle of Pichincha","The Galápagos Islands, which belong to Ecuador, inspired Charles Darwin's theory of evolution","Quito, the capital, sits at about 9,350 feet above sea level, making it one of the highest capitals in the world"]},"China":{"desc":"China has one of the world's oldest continuous civilizations, with over 4,000 years of recorded history. It was ruled by a series of dynasties until the Republic was established in 1912, and the Communist Party under Mao Zedong took power in 1949.","facts":["One of the world's oldest civilizations","Ruled by dynasties for thousands of years","Republic established in 1912 after fall of Qing dynasty","Communist revolution in 1949 under Mao Zedong","Great Wall, gunpowder, paper, compass, and printing are famous Chinese inventions"]},"Napoleon Bonaparte":{"desc":"Napoleon Bonaparte was a French military leader who rose to power during the French Revolution and became Emperor of France. He conquered much of Europe before being defeated at the Battle of Waterloo in 1815 and exiled to Saint Helena.","facts":["Rose to power during the French Revolution","Crowned himself Emperor of France in 1804","Conquered much of Europe through brilliant military campaigns","Defeated at the Battle of Waterloo in 1815","Exiled to Saint Helena where he died in 1821"]},"Puerto Rico":{"desc":"Puerto Rico is an island in the Caribbean that has been a U.S. territory since 1898. Spain controlled it for nearly 400 years before the United States took it over after winning the Spanish-American War.","facts":["The United States acquired Puerto Rico from Spain in 1898 after the Spanish-American War","Puerto Ricans became U.S. citizens in 1917 through the Jones-Shafroth Act","San Juan, the capital, was founded by Spanish settlers in 1521"]},"Los Angeles":{"desc":"Los Angeles is the second-largest city in the United States, located in southern California. It was originally a small Spanish pueblo founded in 1781 and grew into a massive city known for Hollywood, the entertainment industry, and its diverse population.","facts":["Los Angeles was founded on September 4, 1781, by Spanish settlers","The full original Spanish name was 'El Pueblo de los Ángeles' meaning 'The Town of the Angels'","The Hollywood film industry began developing in Los Angeles in the early 1900s"]},"France":{"desc":"France is a major European country with a history spanning thousands of years. It has been central to many of world history's most important events, from the Crusades to the French Revolution to both World Wars.","facts":["One of the oldest nations in Europe","The French Revolution (1789) transformed world politics","Napoleon Bonaparte built a vast European empire","Major participant in both World Wars","Has been a global center of art, culture, and philosophy"]},"Palace of Versailles":{"desc":"The Palace of Versailles is a huge and fancy royal palace near Paris, France, that was built by King Louis XIV in the 1600s. It became the center of French government and a symbol of the incredible wealth and power of French kings before the French Revolution.","facts":["Louis XIV moved the royal court to Versailles in 1682","The famous Hall of Mirrors contains 357 mirrors and is 240 feet long","The Treaty of Versailles, ending World War I, was signed there on June 28, 1919"]},"Margaret Thatcher":{"desc":"Margaret Thatcher was the first female Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, serving from 1979 to 1990. Known as the 'Iron Lady,' she was famous for her strong conservative policies and led Britain during the Falklands War.","facts":["First female Prime Minister of the UK (1979-1990)","Known as the 'Iron Lady' for her tough political style","Led Britain during the Falklands War with Argentina (1982)","Implemented strong free-market economic policies","Longest-serving British PM of the 20th century"]},"John Adams":{"desc":"John Adams was the second President of the United States and one of the key Founding Fathers. He helped draft the Declaration of Independence and served as the first Vice President under George Washington.","facts":["Second President of the United States (1797-1801)","Key Founding Father who helped draft the Declaration of Independence","First Vice President under George Washington","His son John Quincy Adams became the 6th president","Died on July 4, 1826 - the same day as Thomas Jefferson"]},"Japan":{"desc":"Japan is an island nation in East Asia with a rich cultural and military history. It was ruled by emperors and powerful shoguns for centuries, rapidly modernized during the Meiji Restoration of 1868, and became a major world power in the 20th century.","facts":["Island nation in East Asia with over 6,800 islands","Ruled by emperors and shoguns for centuries","Meiji Restoration (1868) rapidly modernized the country","Major power in WWII; atomic bombs dropped on Hiroshima and Nagasaki in 1945","Rebuilt after WWII to become the world's third-largest economy"]},"Battle of Bunker Hill":{"desc":"The Battle of Bunker Hill was one of the first major battles of the American Revolution, fought on June 17, 1775, near Boston. Even though the British won the battle, the American colonists fought so bravely that it gave them confidence they could stand up to the powerful British army.","facts":["The battle was actually fought mostly on Breed's Hill, not Bunker Hill, on June 17, 1775","The British suffered over 1,000 casualties, about twice as many as the Americans","The famous order 'Don't fire until you see the whites of their eyes' is associated with this battle"]},"Great Zimbabwe":{"desc":"Great Zimbabwe was a medieval city in southeastern Africa that was the capital of the Kingdom of Zimbabwe. Its massive stone ruins, built between the 11th and 15th centuries, are the largest ancient structures south of the Sahara Desert.","facts":["Medieval African city built between the 11th and 15th centuries","Capital of the Kingdom of Zimbabwe","Largest ancient stone structures south of the Sahara","Built without mortar - stones fit together precisely","Modern country of Zimbabwe is named after this site"]},"Nikita Khrushchev":{"desc":"Nikita Khrushchev was the leader of the Soviet Union from 1953 to 1964, during some of the most tense years of the Cold War. He is remembered for the Cuban Missile Crisis, banging his shoe at the United Nations, and for criticizing the previous leader Joseph Stalin's harsh rule.","facts":["He gave a famous 'Secret Speech' in 1956 denouncing Stalin's crimes and cult of personality","He led the Soviet Union during the Cuban Missile Crisis of October 1962","He was removed from power in October 1964 by other Communist Party leaders"]},"Tang Dynasty":{"desc":"The Tang Dynasty ruled China from 618 to 907 AD and is considered one of the greatest periods in Chinese history. During this time, China was the most powerful and advanced civilization in the world, with amazing achievements in poetry, art, and technology.","facts":["The Tang Dynasty lasted from 618 to 907 AD, nearly 300 years","The capital city of Chang'an (modern Xi'an) was the largest city in the world with about 1 million people","Woodblock printing was invented during the Tang Dynasty, making books available to more people"]},"Hawaii":{"desc":"Hawaii is a chain of volcanic islands in the Pacific Ocean that became the 50th U.S. state in 1959. The islands were originally settled by Polynesian voyagers and were ruled as an independent kingdom until the Hawaiian monarchy was overthrown in 1893.","facts":["Hawaii became the 50th U.S. state on August 21, 1959","King Kamehameha I united the Hawaiian Islands into one kingdom in 1810","The Hawaiian monarchy was overthrown on January 17, 1893, with the support of American businessmen"]},"Great Salt Lake":{"desc":"The Great Salt Lake is the largest saltwater lake in the Western Hemisphere, located in Utah. It is a remnant of a much larger ancient lake called Lake Bonneville that existed during the last Ice Age, and its water is saltier than the ocean.","facts":["The Great Salt Lake is about 75 miles long and 35 miles wide, though its size changes with water levels","It is a remnant of prehistoric Lake Bonneville, which covered much of western Utah about 30,000 years ago","The lake's salinity ranges from 5% to 27%, much saltier than the ocean's average of 3.5%"]},"IBM":{"desc":"IBM (International Business Machines) is one of the oldest and most important technology companies in the world. Founded in 1911, it played a huge role in the development of computers and helped shape the entire technology industry.","facts":["IBM was founded on June 16, 1911, as the Computing-Tabulating-Recording Company and renamed IBM in 1924","IBM introduced the IBM PC (personal computer) in 1981, which set the standard for modern PCs","IBM's Deep Blue computer famously defeated world chess champion Garry Kasparov in 1997"]},"Australia":{"desc":"Australia is both a country and a continent, located in the Southern Hemisphere surrounded by the Indian and Pacific Oceans. British settlers established a colony there in 1788, and it became an independent nation in 1901 when its six colonies joined together.","facts":["Australia became a federation of six colonies on January 1, 1901","The first British colony was established at Sydney Cove on January 26, 1788, originally as a penal colony","Australia is the world's sixth-largest country by land area"]},"Atlanta":{"desc":"Atlanta is the capital of Georgia and played a major role in both the Civil War and the Civil Rights Movement. During the Civil War, Union General William Sherman captured and burned much of the city in 1864, and a century later it became a center of the fight for equal rights.","facts":["General William T. Sherman captured Atlanta on September 2, 1864, and burned much of it during his March to the Sea","Martin Luther King Jr. was born in Atlanta on January 15, 1929","Atlanta hosted the Summer Olympic Games in 1996"]},"Sioux":{"desc":"The Sioux are a group of Native American peoples who originally lived on the Great Plains of North America. They were skilled buffalo hunters and fierce warriors who famously defeated General Custer at the Battle of the Little Bighorn in 1876.","facts":["The Sioux defeated Lt. Colonel George Custer at the Battle of the Little Bighorn on June 25, 1876","The Sioux Nation includes three major groups: the Lakota, Dakota, and Nakota","The Wounded Knee Massacre on December 29, 1890, killed about 250-300 Sioux men, women, and children"]},"Chicago":{"desc":"Chicago is the third-largest city in the United States, located on the shore of Lake Michigan in Illinois. It grew rapidly in the 1800s as a railroad hub and was nearly destroyed by the Great Chicago Fire of 1871, after which it was rebuilt with innovative new architecture.","facts":["The Great Chicago Fire burned from October 8-10, 1871, destroying about 3.3 square miles of the city","Chicago hosted the World's Columbian Exposition (World's Fair) in 1893","The world's first skyscraper, the Home Insurance Building, was built in Chicago in 1885"]},"Xi Jinping":{"desc":"Xi Jinping is the leader of China, serving as President and General Secretary of the Chinese Communist Party since 2012. He has become the most powerful Chinese leader in decades, and in 2018 he removed presidential term limits so he could stay in power longer.","facts":["Xi Jinping became General Secretary of the Chinese Communist Party in November 2012","In 2018, China's constitution was amended to remove presidential term limits","His father, Xi Zhongxun, was a veteran revolutionary leader and senior Communist Party official"]},"Daniel Boone":{"desc":"Daniel Boone was a famous American frontiersman and explorer who helped open up Kentucky for settlement in the late 1700s. He blazed the Wilderness Road through the Cumberland Gap and founded the settlement of Boonesborough, becoming one of the most legendary figures of the American frontier.","facts":["Boone blazed the Wilderness Road through the Cumberland Gap into Kentucky in 1775","He founded Fort Boonesborough in Kentucky in 1775","He was born on November 2, 1734, in Pennsylvania and died on September 26, 1820, in Missouri"]},"Theodore Roosevelt":{"desc":"Theodore Roosevelt was the 26th President of the United States, known for his energetic personality, conservation efforts, and the construction of the Panama Canal. He was the youngest person to become president at age 42 after McKinley's assassination.","facts":["26th President of the United States (1901-1909)","Youngest president at age 42 after McKinley's assassination","Known as a 'trust buster' who regulated big business","Built the Panama Canal","Created many national parks and forests"]},"Wisconsin":{"desc":"Wisconsin is a state in the upper Midwest of the United States that became the 30th state in 1848. It is known as \"America's Dairyland\" because of its huge dairy farming industry, and it was originally home to many Native American peoples including the Ho-Chunk and Menominee.","facts":["Wisconsin became the 30th state on May 29, 1848","Madison is the state capital, and Milwaukee is the largest city","The Republican Party was founded in Ripon, Wisconsin, in 1854"]},"Belgium":{"desc":"Belgium is a small country in Western Europe that became independent in 1830 and has played an important role in European history. It was a major battleground in both World War I and World War II, and today its capital Brussels serves as the headquarters of the European Union.","facts":["Belgium declared independence from the Netherlands on October 4, 1830","Brussels, the capital, serves as the headquarters of the European Union and NATO","Much of World War I's Western Front was fought in Belgium, including the brutal battles around Ypres"]},"Korean War":{"desc":"The Korean War was fought from 1950 to 1953 between North Korea (supported by China and the Soviet Union) and South Korea (supported by the United States and other UN countries). The war ended in a ceasefire but no peace treaty, so North and South Korea are technically still at war today.","facts":["The war began on June 25, 1950, when North Korea invaded South Korea","About 36,500 American soldiers died in the Korean War","The armistice was signed on July 27, 1953, establishing the demilitarized zone (DMZ) near the 38th parallel"]},"Constantinople":{"desc":"Constantinople was the capital of the Byzantine Empire for over 1,000 years. Founded by Emperor Constantine I in 330 CE on the site of ancient Byzantium, it was the largest and wealthiest city in Europe during the Middle Ages. It fell to the Ottoman Turks in 1453 and was renamed Istanbul.","facts":["Founded by Constantine I in 330 CE","Capital of the Byzantine Empire for over 1,000 years","Largest and wealthiest city in medieval Europe","Fell to the Ottoman Turks under Sultan Mehmed II in 1453","Renamed Istanbul and became the Ottoman capital"]},"Alexander Graham Bell / Telephone (150th Anniversary)":{"desc":"Alexander Graham Bell patented the telephone on March 7, 1876, and made the first phone call three days later, saying 'Mr. Watson, come here, I want to see you.' 2026 marks the 150th anniversary of this invention that changed communication forever. Bell was born in Scotland and moved to Canada, then the United States. He also worked with deaf students, and his mother and wife were both deaf.","facts":["Bell's first words on the telephone were to his assistant Thomas Watson","He demonstrated the telephone at the 1876 World's Fair in Philadelphia","Bell also invented early versions of the metal detector and the photophone","There is debate over whether Elisha Gray invented a similar device at nearly the same time","Bell founded the Bell Telephone Company, which later became AT&T"]},"Mughal Empire / Battle of Panipat (500th Anniversary)":{"desc":"In 1526, Babur defeated Sultan Ibrahim Lodi at the First Battle of Panipat and founded the Mughal Empire in India. 2026 marks the 500th anniversary of this empire, which ruled most of South Asia for over 300 years. The Mughals built the Taj Mahal, the Red Fort, and many other famous monuments. At its peak under Emperor Akbar, the Mughal Empire ruled over 100 million people.","facts":["Babur was a descendant of both Genghis Khan and Timur (Tamerlane)","The word 'Mughal' comes from 'Mongol'","Emperor Shah Jahan built the Taj Mahal as a tomb for his wife Mumtaz Mahal","Emperor Akbar was known for religious tolerance and invited scholars from many faiths","The British East India Company gradually took over Mughal territory starting in the 1700s"]},"Dutch Purchase of Manhattan (400th Anniversary)":{"desc":"In May 1626, Peter Minuit of the Dutch West India Company reportedly purchased the island of Manhattan from the Lenape people. Legend says the price was about 60 guilders worth of trade goods (often described as '$24 worth of beads,' though this is oversimplified). The Dutch colony of New Amsterdam eventually became New York City when the English took it over in 1664.","facts":["The Dutch named their colony New Amsterdam after the capital of the Netherlands","The Lenape people who lived there may not have understood they were 'selling' the land","Wall Street gets its name from a defensive wall the Dutch built","The English renamed it New York after the Duke of York when they took control in 1664","2026 marks the 400th anniversary of this famous transaction"]},"Robert Goddard / First Liquid Rocket (100th Anniversary)":{"desc":"On March 16, 1926, Robert Goddard launched the world's first liquid-fueled rocket from a farm in Auburn, Massachusetts. The rocket flew for only 2.5 seconds and reached 41 feet, but it changed history. 2026 marks 100 years since this flight. Goddard is called the 'father of modern rocketry' and his work paved the way for space travel.","facts":["Goddard's first rocket was powered by liquid oxygen and gasoline","Many people laughed at his idea that rockets could reach the Moon","NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center is named after him","He launched 34 rockets during his lifetime, with the highest reaching 9,000 feet","The New York Times once mocked him, then published a correction — in 1969, when Apollo 11 went to the Moon"]},"Jimmy Carter":{"desc":"Jimmy Carter was the 39th President of the United States (1977-1981). He died on December 29, 2024, at age 100, making him the longest-lived U.S. president ever. After his presidency, Carter spent decades doing humanitarian work, including building houses with Habitat for Humanity. He won the Nobel Peace Prize in 2002 for his work promoting peace and human rights around the world.","facts":["Carter was a peanut farmer from Plains, Georgia before becoming president","He helped negotiate the Camp David Accords peace treaty between Egypt and Israel","He lived to be 100 years old — the first U.S. president to reach that age","He and his wife Rosalynn were married for 77 years, the longest presidential marriage","He was a graduate of the U.S. Naval Academy and served on nuclear submarines"]},"Coronation of King Charles III":{"desc":"Charles III became King of the United Kingdom on September 8, 2022, when his mother Queen Elizabeth II died after 70 years on the throne. His coronation ceremony took place on May 6, 2023, at Westminster Abbey in London. He is the oldest person ever to be crowned British monarch, at age 74. Charles had been the longest-serving heir apparent in British history.","facts":["Queen Elizabeth II reigned for 70 years, the longest reign in British history","Charles waited longer to become king than any previous British monarch","The coronation used the same chair (St Edward's Chair) that has been used since 1308","His wife Camilla was crowned Queen alongside him","Charles is known for his environmental and conservation work"]},"Israel-Hamas War / Gaza Conflict":{"desc":"On October 7, 2023, the militant group Hamas launched a surprise attack on Israel from the Gaza Strip, killing over 1,100 people and taking about 240 hostages. Israel responded with a major military operation in Gaza. The conflict has caused a humanitarian crisis with tens of thousands of casualties and widespread destruction in Gaza. It has been one of the most significant events in the ongoing Israeli-Palestinian conflict.","facts":["Gaza is a small territory on the Mediterranean coast between Israel and Egypt","Hamas has controlled Gaza since 2007","The conflict led to major protests and debates around the world","Many countries have called for a ceasefire and peace negotiations","The Israeli-Palestinian conflict has roots going back to the early 20th century"]},"Henry Kissinger":{"desc":"Henry Kissinger was the U.S. Secretary of State under Presidents Nixon and Ford and one of the most influential diplomats of the 20th century. He died on November 29, 2023, at age 100. He helped open relations between the U.S. and China in 1972 and negotiated the end of American involvement in the Vietnam War. He won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1973 but remained a controversial figure.","facts":["Born in Germany, his family fled the Nazi regime and came to America in 1938","He arranged President Nixon's historic 1972 visit to China","He practiced 'shuttle diplomacy' — flying between countries to negotiate","His policy of 'realpolitik' focused on practical results over idealism","He lived to be 100 years old"]},"Sandra Day O'Connor":{"desc":"Sandra Day O'Connor was the first woman to serve on the United States Supreme Court. She was appointed by President Ronald Reagan in 1981 and served until 2006. She died on December 1, 2023, at age 93. As a moderate conservative, she was often the decisive 'swing vote' on important cases. Before her appointment, she was an Arizona state senator and judge.","facts":["She was confirmed unanimously by the Senate, 99-0","She grew up on a cattle ranch in Arizona called the Lazy B Ranch","Despite graduating near the top of her class at Stanford Law School, she was initially offered only secretarial jobs because she was a woman","She was the first female majority leader of any state senate in the U.S.","She retired to care for her husband, who had Alzheimer's disease"]},"Alexei Navalny":{"desc":"Alexei Navalny was a Russian opposition leader who became famous for fighting corruption in the Russian government and challenging President Vladimir Putin. He died in a Russian prison on February 16, 2024, at age 47. In 2020, he survived a poisoning with a nerve agent that he blamed on the Kremlin. After recovering in Germany, he returned to Russia in 2021 and was immediately arrested.","facts":["He used social media and YouTube videos to expose corruption among Russian officials","He organized some of the largest anti-government protests in modern Russian history","He survived a poisoning with the nerve agent Novichok in 2020","He was sentenced to prison on charges widely seen as politically motivated","His death drew international condemnation from world leaders"]},"2026 FIFA World Cup (US/Canada/Mexico)":{"desc":"The 2026 FIFA World Cup is being hosted jointly by the United States, Canada, and Mexico — the first World Cup held across three countries and the first with 48 teams (expanded from 32). The last time the U.S. hosted the World Cup was in 1994. This tournament is one of the biggest sporting events in the world, with billions of viewers worldwide.","facts":["It's the first World Cup with 48 teams instead of 32","Games will be played in 16 cities across three countries","The final will be held at MetLife Stadium in New Jersey","The 1994 World Cup in the U.S. set attendance records that still stand","Canada is hosting World Cup games for the first time ever"]},"2026 Winter Olympics (Milan-Cortina)":{"desc":"The 2026 Winter Olympics are being held in Milan and Cortina d'Ampezzo, Italy, in February 2026. Italy previously hosted the Winter Olympics in Turin in 2006 and in Cortina in 1956. The games feature sports like skiing, ice hockey, figure skating, and bobsled. Milan is Italy's second-largest city and a world fashion capital.","facts":["Cortina d'Ampezzo is in the Italian Alps and hosted the Winter Olympics once before in 1956","Italy has hosted the Olympics three times total (1956, 1960, and 2006)","The opening ceremony will be held at San Siro Stadium in Milan","The games will feature around 2,900 athletes from over 90 countries","New events being considered include ski mountaineering"]},"Battles of Lexington and Concord (250th in 2025)":{"desc":"On April 19, 1775, the Battles of Lexington and Concord marked the start of the American Revolutionary War. British soldiers marched from Boston to seize colonial weapons stored in Concord, Massachusetts. Minutemen (colonial militia) confronted them at Lexington Green, where 'the shot heard round the world' was fired. The 250th anniversary was celebrated in 2025.","facts":["Paul Revere and William Dawes rode through the night to warn that the British were coming","The first shots were fired at Lexington Green, but nobody knows which side fired first","The colonial militia were called 'minutemen' because they could be ready to fight in a minute","The British retreated back to Boston, harassed by colonial fighters along the road","Ralph Waldo Emerson later called the first shot 'the shot heard round the world'"]},"Fall of Saigon (50th Anniversary in 2025)":{"desc":"On April 30, 1975, North Vietnamese forces captured Saigon, the capital of South Vietnam, ending the Vietnam War. The famous image of helicopters evacuating people from the U.S. Embassy rooftop became a symbol of the war's end. The city was renamed Ho Chi Minh City after the North Vietnamese leader. The 50th anniversary was commemorated in 2025.","facts":["The evacuation, called 'Operation Frequent Wind,' was the largest helicopter evacuation in history","Over 7,000 people were evacuated by helicopter in the final days","The Vietnam War lasted about 20 years and involved over 2.7 million American soldiers","More than 58,000 Americans and millions of Vietnamese were killed in the war","The city is still called Ho Chi Minh City today and is Vietnam's largest city"]},"Donald Trump / 2024 Presidential Election":{"desc":"Donald Trump won the 2024 presidential election, defeating Vice President Kamala Harris and returning to the White House on January 20, 2025. He became only the second U.S. president to serve non-consecutive terms (the first was Grover Cleveland in the 1890s). Trump's return brought major policy changes including new tariffs on international trade.","facts":["Trump is the 45th and 47th President of the United States","Grover Cleveland (22nd and 24th president) was the only other president to serve non-consecutive terms","Kamala Harris was the first woman, first Black person, and first South Asian person to serve as Vice President","The 2024 election saw record voter turnout","Trump's trade policies in 2025 significantly changed global trade relationships"]},"Artificial Intelligence / ChatGPT":{"desc":"Artificial intelligence (AI) became a major topic starting in late 2022 when OpenAI released ChatGPT, a chatbot that could write essays, answer questions, and have conversations. AI technology has rapidly advanced, sparking debates about its impact on jobs, education, and society. Many companies and governments are now working on AI policies and regulations.","facts":["ChatGPT reached 100 million users in just 2 months after launch — the fastest-growing app ever at the time","AI stands for 'artificial intelligence' — machines that can perform tasks that normally require human intelligence","The concept of AI dates back to the 1950s, when Alan Turing proposed the 'Turing Test'","Major AI companies include OpenAI, Google, Anthropic, and Meta","Many schools and universities are debating how to handle AI in education"]},"Turkey-Syria Earthquakes (2023)":{"desc":"On February 6, 2023, two massive earthquakes struck southern Turkey and northern Syria, killing nearly 60,000 people and leaving millions homeless. The main earthquake had a magnitude of 7.8, followed by a 7.5 magnitude aftershock. It was one of the deadliest natural disasters in the region's modern history and caused widespread destruction across both countries.","facts":["The earthquakes destroyed over 160,000 buildings","Turkey sits on major fault lines where tectonic plates meet","International rescue teams from dozens of countries helped with relief efforts","The disaster prompted questions about building safety standards in the region","It was the deadliest earthquake disaster worldwide since the 2010 Haiti earthquake"]},"James Webb Space Telescope":{"desc":"The James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) launched on December 25, 2021, and began sending back stunning images in July 2022. It is the most powerful space telescope ever built and can see deeper into space (and further back in time) than any previous telescope. Named after a former NASA administrator, it orbits the Sun about 1 million miles from Earth.","facts":["JWST cost about $10 billion and took over 20 years to build","Its primary mirror is 21 feet across, made of 18 gold-coated hexagonal segments","It detects infrared light, allowing it to see through dust clouds and observe the earliest galaxies","It orbits at a point called L2, about 1 million miles from Earth","Its images have revealed details about exoplanet atmospheres and the earliest galaxies ever observed"]}};